<HEADLINE> Egypt: Sudan's Return of Egyptian Property Is </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Egypt Tuesday blessed the envisaged
restoration of Egyptian property seized by Sudan as a positive
step towards mending fences between the two Nile neighbors, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Higher Education Mofeed Shehab said the
move is the beginning of redressing warped conditions set in place
by the Sudanese government six years ago which have soured
Egyptian-Sudanese relations.
</P>
<P>
In a step towards improving the long-hit ties with Egypt,
Sudanese President Omar Al-Bashir has given instructions to return
Egyptian property in Khartoum that was confiscated by the Sudanese
government in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Shehab, also minister of state for scientific research, said
the Ministry of Higher Education will closely follow up the
reinstatement of the Egyptian government property, including the
Cairo University Branch in Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has given orders to accept
resident Sudanese students' applications for admission at the
Khartoum branch of the university.
</P>
<P>
According to Sudanese Embassy sources, Al-Bashir's instructions
cover the Cairo University Khartoum Branch, public schools and the
guesthouse of an Egyptian irrigation and hydrological survey team.
 umed the river Nile navigation after a hiatus of three years, a
move hailed by both sides as a good turn after a long period of
deteriorating ties.
</P>
<P>
The neighbors are at odds over a border dispute and have traded
accusations of harboring militants and oppositions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
