<HEADLINE> Arrested S. African Official Suspended from Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Senior South African
Foreign Affairs official Robert Mcbride, arrested in Mozambique
last Monday for alleged gun smuggling, had been suspended on full
pay pending the outcome of a criminal probe against him.
</P>
<P>
Due to the "gravity of the allegations" against Mcbride, the
Foreign Affairs Department had informed him of the intention to
suspend him from duty as director of the Southeast Asia desk, the
department said in a statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mcbride has replied that he understood the need of the
procedure, given the serious nature of the allegations against
him, and he regretted the embarrassment caused to the South
Africa government, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman said the suspension would technically
come into effect at the weekend, as Mcbride had about five days
to respond in writing, South Africa Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the Mozambican criminal investigation, the
department was also conducting an internal inquiry into the
matter, it said.
</P>
<P>
The department reiterated that Mcbride was not on official
government business at the time of his arrest, but was on a
three-day leave.
</P>
<P>
"The South African government recognized that the due process
of law in Mozambique must take its course," it said.
</P>
<P>
The South African government would provide assistance in the
probe if required by the Mozambican authorities, within the
framework of the bilateral agreements between the two countries
to combat cross-border crime.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, President Nelson Mandela's spokesman said the
president was satisfied that cooperation between South Africa and
Mozambique on fighting cross-border crime would continue despite
the Mcbride incident.
</P>
<P>
Mandela was also confident that the cooperation would be
strengthened, the spokesman said after the president was briefed
on the matter by Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi,
who led a top-level delegation to Maputo Monday to discuss the
arrest with the Mozambican authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
