<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Policy Vacuum for European Central Bank Warned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The planned European Central
Bank (ECB) could operate in a policy vacuum if the European Union
(EU) countries fail to coordinate their economic policies,
former European Commission President Jacques Delors said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Delors made the remark Tuesday at a meeting of the
institutional affairs committee of the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said the European economic and monetary union (EMU) would
mark a "qualitative leap" for the EU's institutions, but the ECB
could find itself operating in a policy vacuum.
</P>
<P>
"If the ECB is working in a political vacuum, then I very much
fear it will become a scapegoat and the whole project could be
called into question," he told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ECB, destined to be a very powerful EU body after the EMU
launch next year, will be responsible for exercising monetary
policy with the aim of achieving price stability throughout the 15
EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
Delors also said that under the Maastricht Treaty, the ECB
would have to explain its policies to the public. "It has to be
accountable to the public and explain what it is doing," he said.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament's economic affairs committee is
scheduled to meet this week to approve a report which will ask the
ECB to make regular appearances before the committees of the
parliament, which under the treaty is the only place where ECB is
obliged to publicly explain its actions.
</P>
<P>
The report would be voted on by the whole assembly in early
April, according to EU sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
