<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Competition Among Pakistani Banks to Become Tense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The decision of Pakistan's
central bank to lift control over the exchange rates for the U.S.
dollar against the rupee will have no significant impact on the
dollar-rupee parity in the open market, but will intensify
competition among banks, a senior banker said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The State Bank of Pakistan (SBP), in a move to further relaxing
foreign exchange control, allowed local and foreign banks
operating in the country to determine their own exchange rates for
the dollar against the rupee.
</P>
<P>
The SBP decision will come into effect from March 24. "It
gives exporters and importers an option to choose among banks to
buy dollars at a cheaper price," said Haseeb Saulat, Assistant
Vice President of Askari Commercial Bank LTD in a telephone
interview Tuesday evening. "Thus the competition among banks will
be even tense," he added.
</P>
<P>
 In a circular, the SBP Tuesday announced that it will allow
authorized dealers to quote different exchange rates for U.S.
dollar like other currencies.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also decided to widen its buy and sell spread
for the green back from 0.5 percent to one percent and allowed
banks to quote their own dollar-rupee exchange rates for
transactions.
</P>
<P>
On January 20, SBP allowed authorized dealers to fix their own
rates of exchange for about 24 foreign currencies other than U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani rupee is pegged to the dollar and the Foreign
Exchange Committee has been determining dollar-rupee exchange
rates on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, importers will be free to purchase U.S.
dollar for imports, in ready or forward, from any authorized
dealer like other foreign currencies subject to the procedure and
stipulations of the SBP's announcement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bandits Threatening Somalia's Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The security situation in the
capital here as elsewhere in Somalia is deteriorating since
bandits are rampant in a vicious circle of clan related
animosities.
</P>
<P>
Three people were killed and three others were wounded when a
group of unidentified gunmen ambushed a Toyota pick-up near the
former milk factory of Hodom district Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to an eyewitness account, the gunmen, nearly 10
armed with assault rifles, have indiscriminately opened fire on
the Toyota pick-up, killing two of its occupants on the spot.
</P>
<P>
The deceased included a well known businessman, Ali Ahmed
Hassan, the head of the Cargo section of Daallo Airlines, one of
three major local airline companies operating in Somalia and his
driver.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to the family members of the
deceased, the killing was a retaliatory action carried out by
armed men from the Suleman sub-clan against the Eyr sub-clan,
both belonging to the Habar Gidir clan of Hussein Mohamed Aidid.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the country, another killing has also occurred in
the remote village of Gudinlabe, about 500 km north of Mogadishu
where three men were killed and their car was looted by armed men
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The report did not confirm whether the two killing incidents
were correlated or were just a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
The retaliatory sub-clan-based animosity between the two
groups roots back to the killing of a well-known businessman,
late Qasim Sheikh Mohamud, who was killed by Eyr sub-clansmen
near Ballidogle airport, 90 km Southwest of the capital on
December 25 last year. The businessman was himself killed for a
retaliation purpose.
</P>
<P>
The animosity between the two sub-clans has reach its climax
after an armed confrontation took place between Eyr and Suleman
sub-clansmen in Afgoe district, 30 km South of Mogadishu in mid
February, where at least 12 men were killed and many others
wounded including non combatant civilians.
</P>
<P>
In another incident Tuesday, three people were wounded and a
passenger bus was looted by unidentified gunmen who opened fire
on the bus on the road to Afgoe town.
</P>
<P>
The insecurity in Mogadishu and its surrounding areas is
getting worse with the delay on common understanding between
Mogadishu's faction leaders.
</P>
<P>
These horrible incidents are taking place at a time when
Hussein Aidid is outside Somalia for an unexpected visit to
neighboring Kenya where he was allegedly invited by president
Daniel Arap Moi.
</P>
<P>
Two committees from Hussein Aidid and Ali Mahdi Mohamed have
been holding successive meetings here to end the stalemate over
the formation of a workable mechanism in beginning Mogadishu's
administration.
</P>
<P>
Both sides spoke of optimism in the talks and are expecting
Hussein Aidid to arrive in Mogadishu later today to finalize the
deadlock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
