<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Needs Reinforcement from Other Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian-led west African
peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG said Tuesday it needs troops
contributed by other neighbors to reinforce its final push on
remnants of the dislodged military junta in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Five weeks after ECOMOG removed the junta from power in
Freetown and subsequently captured six other major towns across
Sierra Leone, other west African countries, including Guinea, are
yet to contribute their troops to ECOMOG as promised.
</P>
<P>
The British Broadcasting Corporation quoted a senior Nigerian
ECOMOG officer as saying that the junta remnants in diamond-rich
eastern Sierra Leone are continuing to attack defenseless
civilians.
</P>
<P>
The question of technical protection of the ECOMOG-controlled
areas in the district needs to be addressed, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the officer, Freetown is now safe and well
secured but other countries of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) must contribute their parts to ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
"Troops from other ECOWAS countries and logistics from certain
Western countries would give the right signal as they advance to
capture the remaining towns not necessarily under the control of
the junta," he said.
</P>
<P>
Four weeks ago, Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi said that
Niger was going to contribute 1,000 troops to ECOMOG to assist
their operations.
</P>
<P>
However, the troops are yet to arrive in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigeria's commitment to the operation is signaled
by constant injection of personnel and weaponry, which continues
to build up the country's dominance in the sub-regional force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
