<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kyoto Protocol to U.N. Framework Convention on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Kyoto Protocol to the
United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change opened for
signature Monday at the Headquarters of the United Nations in New
York, the U.N. spokesman's office announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Maldives was the first country to sign, followed by Antigua and
Barbuda, Samoa, Argentina, Saint Lucia and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, adopted in the city of Kyoto, Japan, on December
11, 1997, contains legally binding targets for developed countries
for the post-2000 period that will reduce the emissions levels of
key greenhouse gases, such as carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous
oxide.
</P>
<P>
The protocol will enter into force 90 days after it has been
ratified by at least 55 parties to the convention. These should
include developed countries representing at least 55 percent of
the group's total 1,990 carbon dioxide emissions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
