<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Production Remains Unchanged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. output at the
nation's factories, mines and utilities was unchanged in February,
the Federal Reserve reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The steady level of the output in February followed a revised
0.1 percent growth in January and much bigger increases of 0.3
percent in December and 0.8 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
Unseasonably warm weather nation-wide caused by El Nino
continued to weaken the demand for electricity and natural gas
used in heating. Utilities showed a 0.9 percent rise in February,
as compared with the 3.1 percent drop in January.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing was flat last month following a 0.3 percent
increase in January. Production of autos and light trucks fell by
2.1 percent in February following even bigger declines in January
and December.
</P>
<P>
The monthly record was the first time it has failed to show an
increase since October 1996.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. economy grew at a strong 3.8 percent annual rate in
1997, the best showing in nearly a decade. However, some
economists believe that the growth this year could be a full
percentage point lower as the Asian crisis contributes to slower
manufacturing activity.
</P>
<P>
For February, the unchanged performance in manufacturing
reflected a small 0.1 percent rise in production of durable goods,
items expected to last three or more years. This slight gain was
attributed to strong increases in computers, semiconductors and
office equipment offsetting the weakness in auto production.
</P>
<P>
There was a 0.1 percent decline in production of non-durable
goods. Declines in output of food and paper products outweighed
gains in production of consumer chemicals and residential use of
utilities.
</P>
<P>
The production of business equipment, which had expanded nearly
11 percent last year, fell by 0.2 percent in February after having
an even larger 0.6 percent plunge in January.
</P>
<P>
Similar declines were also seen in the production of
industrial, telephone and photographic equipment.
</P>
<P>
Output at the nation's mines was down 0.3 percent in February
in the wake of a big 1.6 percent increase in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
