<HEADLINE> Perry Sees More R&AMP;D Investment as Important </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Defense Secretary
William Perry said the U.S. needs to do more to preserve its
technology lead.
</P>
<P>
The global dominance of the United States is not assured as it
faces "very tough competition," he said during an interview,
according to the Investor's Business Daily Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Regarding competition between Japan and the U.S., he said
whenever the basis of competition is innovation, the U.S. does
"very well," but when it's manufacturing sills, "usually Japan
wins."
</P>
<P>
"That may be true in the future as it has been in the past,
maybe not," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Japan had a detailed plan to dominate technology,
inventing in memory chips, high-definition television and
artificial intelligence, which it sees as unbeatable areas.
</P>
<P>
"Simply, Japan bet on the wrong horses," he charged.
</P>
<P>
Perry was concerned about the reduction of government funding
for technology as the defense budget, part of it allocated for
technology, has decreased in recent years.
</P>
<P>
An increase of the talent pool, enough capital, access to
international markets, a vital economy and a rise of the research
and development base are the issues that the U.S. must address to
preserve its technology lead, Perry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
