<HEADLINE> 4 Parties Agree to Talks on Korean Peninsula in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The four parties having talks on
the Korean Peninsula have agreed that the talks have now turned
from procedural matters into a phase of discussions on substantial
issues.
</P>
<P>
China, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), South
Korea and the United States of America have also agreed to make
concerted efforts for further progress of the talks, Chen Jian,
assistant foreign minister of China, said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the plenary meeting on the second day, Chen,
chairing the current round of the talks, said that it is necessary
to seek some organizational makeups to have deep discussions on
certain matters.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese side will make positive efforts for
the talks to go on in a smooth way as long as they are in favor of
the peace and stability on the Korean Peninsula and the ultimate
goal of the four-party talks: reaching consensus on a peace treaty
to replace an armistice signed in 1953 when the fighting on the
Korean Peninsula ended.
</P>
<P>
The head of the Chinese delegation said that China will play a
constructive role in helping establish a new peaceful mechanism at
an earliest date.
</P>
<P>
Before the meeting Tuesday afternoon, China had bilateral
consultations with each of the other three delegations.
</P>
<P>
The other three delegations at the second plenary session of
the talks, launched in Geneva last December, are led by DPRK
Deputy Foreign Minister Kim Gye Gwan, South Korean Deputy Foreign
Minister Song Young-Shik, and U.S. Assistant Secretary of State
Stanley Roth.
</P>
<P>
The current round of talks began here Monday and is expected to
last three to five days. 
</P>
