<HEADLINE> World Oil Demand Growth Forecast to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 17 (Xinhua) -- World oil demand is forecast to
reach 75.1 million barrels a day in 1998, representing an increase
of 1.6 million b/d from 1997, when the growth was 1.8 million
barrels b/d.
</P>
<P>
Citing the figures of the International Energy Agency, the U.S.
Journal of Commerce said Tuesday that the slowdown trend is due to
the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Aside from China and India where growth in oil demand is
expected to remain strong, the rest of Asia is expected to see
little growth, the IEA was quoted as saying in its latest monthly
oil market report.
</P>
<P>
On the supply front the IEA said world crude production was
estimated at 76.7 million b/d in February, up 670,000 b/d from
January.
</P>
<P>
Non-OPEC oil supply last month was estimated at 45 million b/d,
while crude from members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries was about 28.8 million b/d, up from 28.1
million b/d in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
