<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Cuts Short His Meeting With Cook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Banjamin
Netanyahu has cut short his meeting here Tuesday evening with
visiting British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook as planned,
Netanyahu's office said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu also decided not to host a dinner in
honor of Cook as formerly planned, the office added.
</P>
<P>
The office did not give the reason why Netanyahu has decided to
do so, but it is believed here that Netanyahu is apparently not
happy with Cook's outcome of talks with Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat in Gaza and his
controversial visit to Har Homa earlier Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Arafat, Cook told a press conference
that the European Union opposes Israel's policy of settlement
expansion in the occupied Palestinian territories, which is one
of the main reasons hindering the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He urged Israel to speed up its troop redeployment in the
West Bank and halt all settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
Cook, as a representative of the European Union (EU), is on a
tour of the Middle East aimed at helping revive the peace
process. He has visited Egypt and Jordan before he came to the
Palestinian self-rule areas and Israel. He will also travel to
Syria and Lebanon. Britain is holding the rotating presidency of
the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cook's insistence on seeing for himself Har Homa angered
Israel, which warned that the visit might undermine EU's role in
mediating the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Cook's visit to Har Homa in Arab East Jerusalem also caused
sharp reactions from the Israeli side, saying the visit could only
result in more conflicts between Israelis and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israel broke ground for the construction of a Jewish settlement
on Har Homa a year ago, leading to a standstill in the peace talks
between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel stated that Har Homa is part of Jerusalem and Jerusalem
is the capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Cook's visit to Har Homa, Nabil Shaath, PNA
Minister of Planning and International Cooperation, said that
Cook's visit is a challenge to the Israeli government because it
had tried to convince him not to do so.
</P>
<P>
This is a clear refusal on the part of the Europeans and the
British refusing settlements on Har Homa in particular and
against the policy of settlements in general, Shaath said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
