<HEADLINE> Annan's Visit to Enhance Mideast Peace: Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Tuesday expressed
confidence in the upcoming visit of United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan to the Middle East, saying it will give a
better chance to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt has great confidence in the secretary general and his
mission as well as the role of the United Nations," Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters on the eve of Annan's
tour of the region.
</P>
<P>
"His visit to Egypt acquires a special importance with regard
to chances for reaching a peaceful settlement in the Middle East,"
Moussa added.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to arrive in Cairo on Wednesday, starting his
nine-day trip, which will also take him to Syria, Lebanon, Israel,
the Palestinian self-rule areas and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to hold talks with Moussa and the Arab League
Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid on Wednesday and Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They will focus on the peace talks between the Palestinians,
Syrians and Lebanese, on the one hand, and the Israelis, on the
other, regional and international issues and the U.N. reform,
according to Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Moussa warned that if the Mideast peace process fails, it will
affect peace, security and stability in the area.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Israel and its Arab neighbors have been in a
standstill for more than a year due to Israel's hardline policy
and Jewish settlement activities in the occupied lands.
</P>
<P>
"What concerns us is to support the role of the United Nations
to establish and preserve peace, particularly following the big
push which the U.N. received after Annan's successful mission in
Iraq," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
A deal Annan struck with Baghdad in February averted a possible
military strike against Iraq by the United States and paved the
way for unrestricted U.N. arms inspections of suspected Iraqi
sites. 
</P>
