<HEADLINE> Russia, Moldavia to Increase Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin and his visiting Moldavian counterpart, Ion Ciubuc,
agreed to launch economic cooperation between the two countries
for the period 1999-2008, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said he is satisfied with the current relations
between Russia and Moldavia, which are stable enough for the two
countries to plan their cooperation for a 10-year span and "to
move ahead in the economic and political spheres."
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the complicated problem concerning
the settlement in the Dniester region. They agreed to hold a
meeting in the Black Sea port of Odessa on March 20 to discuss
specific details of the settlement process, the Russian premier
said.
</P>
<P>
The half-hour talks resulted in signing an agreement to
encourage and mutually protect capital investments, as well as a
joint statement on the economic cooperation program to be launched
in the near future, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Another report quoted the Moldavian prime minister as saying
that Moldavia is going to pay off its gas debt to Russia in cash
and exports of goods.
</P>
<P>
Ciubuc had talks on the gas debt with leaders of the Russian
gas giant Gazprom Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Moldavia owes a total of 594 million dollars for natural gas
imports in 1996-1998, of which 159 million is a penalty for
delayed payment.
</P>
<P>
Of the debt the breakaway Dniester enclave accounts for 388
million dollars. The Dniester region paid some 14 percent of its
gas debt in 1994 and 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
