<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Stresses Importance of Girls' Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Minister of
Education Genet Zewdie said on Tuesday that promoting education
of women will enhance the country's human resources capacity.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting here on the importance of girls'
education in the country, Genet underlined that without the
empowerment of women, who constitute 50 percent of the nation's
labour force, development of the country's manpower resources is
unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
She said that special attention should be paid to higher
enrollment of women in education so as to achieve the desired
goal in building up the nation's human resources.
</P>
<P>
She also noted that many Ethiopian women, particularly those
living in rural areas, have been denied their right to get access
to education due to social and cultural reasons. But she said
that the government has a plan to raise the enrollment rate of
women students at all levels of education to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, she said, an extensive program has been launched
nationwide with an eye to raise the awareness of parents of the
importance of girls' education.
</P>
<P>
With regards to female teachers, the education minister said
that mechanisms have been drawn to make female teachers account
for at least 30 percent in every teachers' training institution.
</P>
<P>
Although Ethiopia implements a ten-year compulsory education
system across the country, the number of girls receiving
schooling is far less than that of boys, especially in rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
A recent study shows that illiteracy rate of the female is
higher than that of the male in the surveyed regions in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
For instance, in sampled areas of the northern rural Amhara,
61.1 percent of the male population are illiterate while 79.0
percent of the female are illiterate. In Gambella region, the
female illiterates are nearly 20 percent more than the male
illiterates. And the illiterate rates of the male and the female
in Afar region are 73.7 percent and 81.0 percent respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
