<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Semiconductor Market Forecast to Grow 8.4 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide semiconductor revenue
is forecast to grow 8.4 percent to 148.7 billion U.S. dollars this
year, according to International Data Corporation of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
With memory revenue expected to rebound in 1999, the market
will return to double-digit growth rates, eventually reaching
272.4 billion dollars by 2002, IDC said in its newly published
Semiconductor Market Forecast and Review 1997-2002.
</P>
<P>
IDC revised its 1998 semiconductor market growth projection
from a mid-1997 estimate of 15.1 percent to the new level as it
sees a 9.7 percent decline this year in the memory market to 26.5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
It attributed the situation to "a lingering overcapacity" and
"uncertainty across every region" caused by waves sent by the
Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Japan is most of concern where a 4.8 percent market growth is
forecast, IDC said.
</P>
<P>
However, IDC believes that stable prices as a result of major
capacity cutbacks in combination with strong bit growth will drive
memory revenue up in 1999 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
IDC sees microprocessor segment as a bright spot for the
semiconductor market, expecting its revenue to expand 24.9 percent
to 29.3 billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
On the regional semiconductor trends, IDC said the U.S. market
will reach revenues of 94.5 billion dollars in 2002, while
European consumption share will remain flat throughout the
forecast period.
</P>
<P>
Asia Pacific region will surpass Japan in revenue size by 1999,
it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
