<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Refuses to Budge on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Reacting angrily to British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook's Har Homa visit, Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Tuesday said Israel would never
accepts a redivision of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking alone to reporters following a tense meeting with
Cook, Netanyahu said Israel would never relinquish its sovereign
claim over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In protest of Cook's visit to Arab East Jerusalem's Har Homa,
where Israel is building a settlement, Netanyahu canceled a
scheduled dinner with the British minister.
</P>
<P>
"Israel will never ever accept the redivision of Jerusalem. We
will never build a Berlin Wall inside our city. This is our
eternal city for 3,000 years, we reunited it in a miraculous event
in 1967 ... we will never divide that city," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
Israel took over East Jerusalem in the 1967 Middle East
war and then annexed it; the Palestinians want East Jerusalem as
the capital of their future state.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that during their one-hour meeting at the Prime
Minister's Office he stressed the Israeli position to Cook, who is
touring the Middle East representing the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu claimed that Israel retains sovereignty over
Jerusalem before the final-status under the signed peace
agreements, and it would not give up its sovereignty even after
the permanent talks.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel welcomed all governments, including European
ones, to participate in advancing the peace process, provided that
they would not take "predetermined and prejudiced positions."
</P>
<P>
He was apparently referring to Cook's position of supporting
the Palestinian demand for a halt to Israeli settlement activities
in occupied Arab lands.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu added that he was waiting to welcome British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, who is expected to visit Israel next
month. He called Blair as "a friend of Israel, a statesman who
wants to move peace forward."
</P>
<P>
Cook's visit to Har Homa and meeting with Palestinian
officials in the Orient House, the de facto Palestinian National
Authority's office in East Jerusalem, were aimed at sending a
strong message to Israel that it must halt settlement expansion in
order to advance peace.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a separate news conference in a Jerusalem hotel,
Cook said that the international community has the "legitimate
concern" about Israel's settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
Israel's start of constructing the Har Homa settlement one
year ago led to a stalemate in Israeli-Palestinian peace talks and
remains a major obstacle to any progress in the renewed
negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
