<HEADLINE> Clinton Demands Insurance Violations Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday ordered Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala
to investigate reported violations of a 1996 law aimed at
guaranteeing health insurance to those who change jobs or lose
coverage.
</P>
<P>
At the Capitol to push his plan to extend Medicare coverage,
Clinton pointed to a new report showing that insurance companies
were finding ways to thwart the law authored by Senator Edward
Kennedy and former Senator Nancy Kassebaum Baker.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "We see that some insurers are finding ways
around that law, giving insurance agents incentives to delay or
deny coverage to vulnerable Americans. These practices have to be
stopped.... We intend to enforce it vigorously."
</P>
<P>
The report by the General Accounting Office (GAO), an
investigative arm of Congress, found that people who exercised
their rights under the law were often charged premiums far higher
than the standard rates. And the GAO said some companies
discouraged insurance agents from selling policies to people with
medical problems, the very people who were supposed to benefit
from the law.
</P>
<P>
The law was supposed to guarantee that people losing group
health insurance would have access to coverage in the individual
insurance market, regardless of pre-existing medical problems.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the government would also notify every insurer in
every state in the country that it is illegal for them to penalize
agents who sell policies to high-risk individuals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
