<HEADLINE> Former Zairean Generals Allowed to Stay in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Three former Zairean
generals were granted leave in the Johannesburg High Court on
Tuesday to stay in South Africa until April 21.
</P>
<P>
Justice M. Joffe said that the generals, who have been living
in South Africa since May last year, had 10 days to apply for
political refugee status which would enable them to stay in the
country legally. And their application will be heard on April 21.
</P>
<P>
Former Zairean defense minister Admiral Mavua Mnoima, General
Kpama Baramoto and General Ngbate Nzinloi fled in May last year
to South Africa after former Zairean president Mobutu Sese Seko
was ousted by the then rebel leader Laurent Kabila who is now
President of the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The three generals were allegedly carrying diamonds and
millions of US dollars when they arrived in South Africa. They
are living in Johannesburg, but their exact whereabouts are not
known.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that at least 120 high-ranking officials of
the former Zairean regime headed by Mobutu are living in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Most of these Zaireans were senior officers or civil servants,
and 102 of them are on a "wanted" list issued by the Kabila
government in connection with the looting of state coffers.
</P>
