<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Vows to Control Its Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran is determined to control its
population growth through family planning and to keep the growth
rate at around 1.5 percent by the end the century.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Deputy Health Minister Ali Akbar Sayadi made the remarks
in an exclusive interview with Xinhua correspondent here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Underlining the importance of family planning programs, Sayadi
said, "we will see a sharp growth of our population in the coming
years, because 51 percent of our people are under 20 and only four
percent of the population are above 65."
</P>
<P>
The government's family planning programs enjoyed a "bright
success" during the recent years by bringing down the population
growth rate from 3 percent in 1950s to 1.4 in 1996, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that each Iranian couple had an average of five
children in 1992, but the number dropped to 2.5 in 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran targeted its population in the year of 2022 at 90 million,
30 million more than the present number and it will try to bring
down the population growth rate to 0.5 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The country started its family planning programs in the 1970s
before the Islamic Revolution in 1979, but the programs were
abandoned because of the revolution and the following Iran-Iraq
war (1980-88), he said.
</P>
<P>
After the war, the Iranian government found it difficult to
meet the demand of the growing population, he said, so the
government started its family planning programs in 1989 together
with the first five-year development plan (1989-1995).
</P>
<P>
Sayadi attributed the success in control the population growth
to the government planning, investments, free-charge services and
international cooperation. Economic difficulties also made people
to abandon the traditional views of having more children, he added.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, more and more people voiced their readiness to
cooperate with the government in family planning, he said, adding
that at present 55 percent of Iranian women accept safe
contraceptives, compared with only 24 percent who agreed to use
them when the government began to carry out the programs.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the country still faces some difficulties in
implementing the programs, saying that one of the serious problems
is that Iranian men showed less interest than women in family
planning.
</P>
<P>
Sayadi termed low-level education of the people, low efficiency
of some government institutions and religious views as other
hurdles for family planning in the country.
</P>
<P>
Although late supreme leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini agreed
with family planning, however, he said, so far no religious
authorities have officially announced family planning as legal.
</P>
<P>
The deputy health minister stressed that the government will
encourage the people to support family planning through education
and propagation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he reiterated that abortion will not permitted in
Iran in the name of family planning, saying that abortion is not
acceptable from the Islamic view and it is not the right means for
population control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Chancellor Unveils "New Ambitions for Britain" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 17 (Xinhua) - British Chancellor Gordon Brown
Unveiled what he called 1998 "New Ambitions For Britain" budget
Tuesday aiming at boosting employment, rewarding families and
helping business.
</P>
<P>
Brown told House of Commons that the Budget is designed to link
four key elements of the Government's economic strategy:
</P>
<P>
-- Securing economic stability based on low inflation and
sound government finances for the long-term;
</P>
<P>
-- Encouraging work by extending the New Deal, making work pay,
providing child care support, tackling skill shortages and
promoting life-long learning;
</P>
<P>
-- Promoting enterprise through a range of tax reforms to boost
investment and small firms; and
</P>
<P>
-- Creating a fairer society, now and in the future.
</P>
<P>
In order to secure economic stability, the budget confirms
inflation target at 2.5 percent. But the Chancellor admitted that
the Government still needs to guard against risks to avoid return
to "boom and bust".
</P>
<P>
For the purpose of promoting long-term investment in British
economy, Brown said investors who hold assets for at least 10
years before selling them would pay capital gains tax of just 24
percent instead of 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Chancellor also said, alongside the move to quarterly
payments and the abolition of Advance Corporation tax main rate
cut for larger companies to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Business investment will also be boosted by confirmation of a
cut in corporation tax to 30 percent from 31 percent and a pledge
it will not rise for the rest of the five-year life of the current
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Brown promised that all families with a full-time worker would
be guaranteed income of 180 pounds a week, with no income tax
payable on incomes to 220 pounds a week.
</P>
<P>
"The budget... begins the task of modernizing not just taxation
but the entire tax and benefits system of our country," he said.
</P>
<P>
In creating a "fairer society", Brown said that the Government
will allocate an extra 500 million pounds (800 million US dollars)
for health next year and 250 million Pounds (400 million US
dollars) for education.
</P>
<P>
The Government will also spend 500 million pounds (800 million
US dollars) at public transport and cutting the annual road
license fee for the cleanest and smallest cars.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Budget, William Hague, leader of the
Conservative party, said: "There is a betrayal and a great deal of
disappointment for many people."
</P>
<P>
The Confederation of British Industry (CBI) gave a broad
welcome overall to the Budget. It's Director-General, Adair
Turner, said: "We are encouraged by the overall fiscal balance and
the prudent approach to public spending... " 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
