<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Compromises for Peace on N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday urged key players in the Northern Ireland talks to make
tough compromises for peace.
</P>
<P>
"Concessions that today might seem hard to accept will seem so
much less important in the light of an accord that brings hope and
peace and an end to violence," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"No one will be the loser if agreement is reached," noted
Clinton at a ceremony to mark the St. Patrick's Day in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
Clinton urged all the parties involved in the Northern Ireland
peace process to demonstrate "by words and deeds" that they reject
violence.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was meeting with different parties which represent
pro-British Protestants and Catholics on the Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"I will say it as clearly and as emphatically as I possibly
can. This is the chance of a lifetime for peace in Ireland. You
must get it done," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Later, the president went to Capitol Hill to attend a St.
Patrick's Day luncheon. He was to end the day playing host to a
White House reception honoring the holiday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday night Clinton met Gerry Adams, leader of the Sinn
Fein party, and Adam's chief negotiator, Martin McGuinness.
</P>
<P>
Adams said he was impressed with Clinton's grasp of the
details. He said he believes prospects for a peace agreement are
good but he could not say that no more violence would mar the
process.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks began in June 1996 and are supposed to end in
May, hopefully with a plan of governance for Northern Ireland
acceptable to both its Protestant majority and the large Catholic
minority.
</P>
<P>
Adams said he is uncertain whether agreement can be reached by
May and he expects no breakthrough in Washington.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials recognize that any real progress will only come
at the Belfast talks and hope that the contacts in Washington will
help create more flexibility.  
</P>
</TEXT>
