<HEADLINE> Cook Defends His Visit to Disputed Har Homa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook defended his visit to the controversial Har
Homa on Tuesday, saying Israel has no reason to overreact.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after a meeting with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Cook said he intended to underline
that Israel's settlement activities in the occupied territories
undermine the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
European Union's attitude towards Israel's expansion of
settlements is in line with that of the United states, as
Washington as well asks Israel to halt such activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cook, representing the European Union (EU), on Tuesday
afternoon visited Har Homa in Arab East Jerusalem the Palestinians
want as their future capital. Britain is holding the rotating
presidency of the EU.
</P>
<P>
Israel broke ground for the construction of a settlement on the
site a year ago. This led to a standstill in the peace talks
between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians accuse Israel of violating the signed
agreements, which they contend prohibit unilateral actions prior
to final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Displeased with Cook's insistence to visit Har Homa, Netanyahu
cut short their meeting and canceled a dinner in his honor in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
But Cook said he felt no sorry to lose a dinner, and that the
international community has a legitimate concern of Israel's
settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
Terming his meeting with Netanyahu as useful, Cook said the
Israeli prime minister told him that the EU has a role to play in
reviving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
During the day, the British top diplomat also held talks with
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, which he said focused
on Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He said he would convey Israel's stance on the issue to
Lebanese and Syrian leaders when he travels to the two countries
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cook arrived here Tuesday for a one-day visit as part of his
regional tour aimed at helping reactivate the peace process. He
has visited Egypt, Jordan and the Palestinian self-rule areas, and
will continue his trip from here to Syria and Lebanon. 
</P>
