<HEADLINE> EU Under Pressure to Carry Study on Duty-Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Ireland Tuesday won support for
its call for a study on the jobs impact of a decision by the
European Commission to end duty-free sales of goods in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Ireland called for a report on the consequences of the
abolition planned by the European Union (EU)'s executive body at a
meeting of EU transport ministers in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Transport ministers from some eight other EU member states
voiced their support for such a report, which is also supposed to
probe into the effects on transport costs of the planned scrapping
of duty-free.
</P>
<P>
An Irish statement cited industry figures estimating between
30,000 to 50,000 job losses if the EU goes ahead and ends
duty-free sales.
</P>
<P>
Irish Minister for Public Enterprise, Mary O'Rourke, stressed
at Tuesday's meeting that the duty-free sector was important for
employment.
</P>
<P>
"The position is quite clear. The transport ministers would
like it to be studied and will communicate that to the finance
ministers," said British Transport Minister Gavin Strang.
</P>
<P>
The International Duty Free Confederation, a lobby group
representing the duty-free industry, said the transport ministers
had sent a "very strong message" to the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
However, the unanimous backing of the finance ministers of the
15 EU member countries is needed to reverse the decision by the
Commission to end duty-free sales of goods such as tobacco and
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
In addition, EU Tax Commissioner Mario Monti has said he sees
no need for such an impact study, adding that he would not bow to
pressure of the duty-free industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
