<HEADLINE> S. Africa Fails to Meet Macroeconomic Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Few of the macroeconomic
targets set out by the South African government have been met,
South Africa Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
According to figures presented to parliament's Finance
Committee Tuesday by Finance Ministry director-general Maria
Ramos, the economic growth in 1997 was only 1.7 percent. The
target set out in the Growth, Employment and Redistribution
(GEAR) macroeconomic strategy was 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Real private investment rose just three percent instead of the
targeted 9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The fiscal deficit was targeted at four percent of the gross
domestic product (GDP), but it came in at 4.3 percent. Real
government consumption went up to 21 percent of the GDP from the
targeted 19.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Formal non-agricultural sector employment was supposed to
increase by three percent, but declined by one percent instead.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that on the positive side, the real effective
exchange rate appreciated by one percent, instead of depreciating
by 0.3 percent, while real non-gold export growth was 9.3 percent
instead of the expected eight percent.
</P>
<P>
Other positive factors were that the annualized inflation was
8.6 percent instead of 9.7 percent, and the current account
deficit was 1.5 percent instead of two percent of the GDP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
