<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Have High Expectations on New Cabinet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Members of China's paramount
power body said here today that they had opted for a compact but
more competent, pragmatic and energetic new cabinet, which they
believe will have a superb performance in advancing the country's
reform, opening-up and modernization drive at the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 3,000 deputies to the Ninth National People's Congress
(NPC), the top legislature, in session here since early March,
today approved by ballotage a list of members of the State
Council, the Chinese cabinet, nominated by the newly-appointed
Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers share the view that the central government of a
new term shoulders great responsibilities and faces great
challenges.
</P>
<P>
Headed by Premier Zhu Rongji, the new cabinet consists of four
vice-premiers, five state councillors and 29 ministers. Records
show that among the ministers, 24 received university education,
eight are granted with senior technical titles, and five have had
experiences of studying or working overseas.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the new cabinet are educated better still than
their predecessors, and experienced with sound records of
administration," said Legislator Zhang Zhongli, 77, who has served
as an NPC deputy for four consecutive terms.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, who is president of the Shanghai Academy of Social
Sciences, also praised these new cabinet members as "having clear
and wide vision and pioneering spirit" and "underlining practical
work".
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Lu Xueyi, a sociologist with the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences, China's reforms have now entered a
critical stage in which some in-depth contradictions are required
to be resolved, while the country's economic and social growth
also needs to be further promoted.
</P>
<P>
"When the new central government makes a good start with a
competent and pragmatic image, it will surely win the people's
support and trust," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet, which has reduced its principal officials by
two vice-premiers, three state councillors and 11 ministers as
compared with the previous one, is the central government with the
fewest officials, since China launched its reform and opening-up
drive two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
Apart from seven ministers in the previous cabinet who have
retained their posts, 17 of the 22 new ministers have been
promoted from among the former vice-ministers, and five others
were transferred from other units.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Have High Expectations on New Cabinet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I'm very glad to see that the new cabinet has been formed in
strict compliance with the institutional restructuring plan, which
was submitted by the State Council to the current NPC session.
This represents the first step so far taken in downsizing
government institutions and changing their functions," said Deputy
Li Yukun, a prestigious artist from east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Qin Chijiang, secretary-general of the Chinese Monetary
Society, said the most urgent task for the Chinese government at
present is to go all out for institutional restructuring, and
reforming the banking sector and state-owned enterprises while
maintaining a steady and rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Qin and a number of other lawmakers said that they have faith
in the competence of the central government of a new term.
</P>
<P>
As the executive vice-premier in charge of economic work in the
previous cabinet, they noted, Zhu Rongji has managed the
macro-control over the national economy in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
It was also Zhu who advocated last year that China should
manage to bring its loss-making large and medium-sized state
enterprises out of troubles and initially set up a modern
financial system to gear to the growth of a market economy in
about three years, they underlined.
</P>
<P>
Among the vice-premiers, they said, Li Lanqing, Qian Qichen and
Wu Bangguo have all scored remarkable success in the fields they
have been assigned to during their tenure of office in the
previous government, while Wen Jiabao, who entered the central
government a dozen years ago, has long proven himself a pragmatic
and knowledgeable person.
</P>
<P>
Many lawmakers expressed the hope that the new central
government will strive for new progress in resolving problems with
the growing public concerns, such as improving the life of the
people in great need and public security and curbing the spread of
corruption.
</P>
<P>
"This is an extremely arduous task for the new cabinet," said
Deputy Feng Qifu, commissioner of Luliang Prefecture in north
China's Shanxi Province, an outlying, backward mountainous region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
