<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrialization, Second Leap in China's Rural Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China's rural economy is
beginning to experience its second leap forward -- the
industrialization of agriculture, according to deputies from some
grain growing areas to the Ninth National People's Congress, in
session here since early March.
</P>
<P>
The first leap forward is known as the household contract
responsibility system, or household-based farming, introduced two
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
The aim of promoting the industrialization of agriculture is to
raise the efficiency of agriculture and enable farmers to get more
added value from the processing and marketing of their farm
produce, according to Qi Jingfa, a vice-minister of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The central government has since 1996 spent 177 million yuan
building the first group of 22 projects for agricultural
industrialization in 12 provinces and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, 10 ministries jointly designated 59 pilot
areas for experimenting with agricultural industrialization, which
are expected to be completed in three years.
</P>
<P>
Farmers have realized that they should not only immerse
themselves in production but also keep an eye on a changing market
for what they produce, said He Chengguo, mayor of Chuzhou, Anhui
province, where household-based farming was first introduced.
</P>
<P>
Industrialization of agriculture makes it possible to break
down barriers between rural and urban areas, promote the interflow
of labor and optimize rural production structures, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ye Liansong, governor of north China's Hebei Province, said the
key to upgrading the rural production structure is to develop key
processing enterprises and intermediate organizations.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Hebei have made much progress in this direction,
according to the governor. They have, for example, set up more
than 10,000 associations specializing in the cultivation,
transportation and selling of farm products such as cotton, water
melons and vegetables.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait, Brazil Sign Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait and Brazil on
Wednesday signed a cooperation agreement on removing trade
barriers and enhancing bilateral trade relations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by visiting Chairman of the
Brazilian-Arab Chamber of Commerce Orlando Sarhan, who arrived
here Tuesday on a four-day visit at the head of a Brazilian trade
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Sarhan told reporters that his visit is intended to foster
bilateral commercial ties, strengthen trade exchanges and attract
investment from the oil-rich Gulf state.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is world's largest coffee producer and rich in natural
resources. It enjoys political stability and suitable economic
atmosphere, an official of the Kuwaiti Chamber of Commerce said.
</P>
<P>
It is one of the most favorable markets for investment
worldwide, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's annual import from Brazil is estimated at 65 million
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
