<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft To Set up Training Centers in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft, the leading
U.S. software producer, signed a cooperation agreement with the
Shanghai municipal government today to set up hundreds of
authorized training centers in the city.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of the training centers will step up the
training of software professionals to promote the wider use of
advanced software," said Pieter Knook, vice president of the far
eastern branch of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft will provide standard Chinese educational software
and teaching materials at preferential prices for the training
centers, and the computer application office of the Shanghai
municipal government will supervise the operation of the training
centers, according to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft has set up 150-plus authorized training centers in
more than 40 Chinese cities with more than 400,000 people
receiving the training.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft invested 10 million U.S. dollars in establishing a
technical support center in Shanghai early this year, the first in
China and the fifth in the world. It also has participated in the
building of the Shanghai information port and the information
system of the Shanghai Pudong Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The software giant has 500 authorized software suppliers in
China, offering technical support for more than 60 software
developers and big customers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Freight Train Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China's first freight train
today left Guangzhou, capital of Guangdong Province, for Beijing
and Shenyang in north China.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Railways said that this is the
start of a new freight-carrying system instead of linking package
cabins with passenger trains.
</P>
<P>
It takes only 36 hours for the freight train from Guangzhou to
Beijing, 20 to 30 hours faster than automobiles, and the price is
cheaper, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Some 283 such trains are expected to be in operation before
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
