<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Manned Spacecraft By Chen Jie and Li Xiguang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China will launch a manned
spacecraft including a lunar explorer in the near future, a
leading Chinese space scientist said here today.
</P>
<P>
"China is striving to make breakthroughs in manned space flight
technology at the end of this century or the beginning of the next
century, and will launch small lunar explorer when possible," Ma
Xingrui, vice-president of the Chinese Academy of Space Technology
(CAST) told an international meeting of space scientists here today.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the CAST, the country's satellite and
spacecraft developing and manufacturing center, Ma disclosed
China's new space program which includes:
</P>
<P>
-- Developing communication satellites of large-capacity,
high-power and long-life to provide direct broadcast, mobile
communication and multi-media communication;
</P>
<P>
-- To develop environmental resources satellites and ocean
satellites. China plans to develop new remote sensor and expand
remote sensing spectrums based on Zi Yuan-1 satellite and develop
ocean satellites;
</P>
<P>
-- To further utilize and improve recoverable satellite to
explore space microgravity rescues. China will use recoverable
satellites continuously to conduct life science experiments and
material processing research under microgravity environment;
</P>
<P>
-- To provide piggyback services for customers throughout the world;
</P>
<P>
-- To develop other spacecrafts on the basis of recoverable
satellite technology;
</P>
<P>
-- To develop small and low-cost satellites to meet the
requirements of space exploration and international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal for space exploration is to set up several application
satellite systems which are badly needed by national economy and
can operate stably for a long term," Ma said.
</P>
<P>
He said that to achieve this purpose, China must keep certain
satellites in orbit by prolonging the operating life of orbital
satellites as much as possible and launching replacement satellite
in time before the orbital satellites come to its end, so as to
ensure the continuity of satellite application.
</P>
<P>
"China will also develop new satellites and some new types of
other spacecrafts to meet the demands of domestic users and try to
make contribution to the development of world's economy, science
and technology," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that China will put priority on satellite payload
technology, and sophisticate satellite platform technology.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the China Aerospace Corporation (CASC),
has established complete systems for research, design,
development, production and testing in various space products such
as launch vehicles and space craft.
</P>
<P>
The corporation, with nearly 10,000 research scientists has
ranked itself among the world's leading space industries in some
of the main areas in space technology, including satellite
recovery, launching multiple payloads with one rocket, launching
geostationary orbit satellite. It has also developed the strategic
missile systems.
</P>
<P>
The China Academy of Launch Vehicle Technology, with a staff of
27,000 researchers and engineers, has developed the Long March
Vehicle Family which has successfully placed more than 40 Chinese
and international satellites into orbit, bringing China's launch
vehicle technology to the world's advanced level.
</P>
<P>
China's space scientists have entered collaboration with their
counterparts in the United States, Japan, Canada and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Space scientists from the US, Japan and Europe are expected to
discuss the latest space technology and international cooperation
in the 21st century with the Chinese researchers during the
three-day conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
