<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10,000 Spindles Destroyed in Zhejiang Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DINGHAI (ZHEJIANG), March 18 (Xinhua) -- After eight hammers
wrapped in red silk swooped down, 10,000 old spindles were
destroyed at Zhoushan Island in East China's Zhejiang Province
today in the continuing national campaign to shrink the textile
industry.
</P>
<P>
China's textile industry has been plagued by overproduction and
chronic inefficiency in recent years. The industry is taking
severe steps to cut down its bloated scale.
</P>
<P>
Ye Rongbao, deputy governor of Zhejiang, said that both the
provincial government and the province's textile firms support the
central government's decision and will proceed with spindle
reduction.
</P>
<P>
Ye, who witnessed today's destruction of the spindles, said the
province has destroyed 250,000 old spindles in the last six years.
</P>
<P>
Su Weiping, an official of the Zhoushan Cotton Mill, claimed
that the pain of losing these spindles will only be temporary
because the company's future development depends on a structural
readjustment in the textile industry.
</P>
<P>
The shattered pieces of the spindles were promptly loaded on
five trucks to be carried away and melted.
</P>
<P>
The whole process was closely scrutinized by an official with
the China National Textile Council.
</P>
<P>
Ma Haijian, factory director of Zhoushan Cotton Mill, received
a 1.5 million yuan check from a representative of the provincial
government as compensation for destroying the spindles.
</P>
<P>
The CNTC official said that another 1.5 million yuan will be
allocated to the mill by the central government.
</P>
<P>
The mill will also obtain two million yuan in low-interest
loans.
</P>
<P>
China plans to reduce 4.8 million outmoded spindles this
year. Since February, more than 220,000 spindles have been
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
CNTC had ruled that every mill must have its spindle reduction
completely scrutinized, starting from application to the actual
hammering and melting.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-March, the CNTC has sent more than 30 inspection
teams to localities to supervise specific implementation of the
spindle reduction and compensation policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
