<HEADLINE> HK Legislators Approve Budget for 1998-99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Provisional legislators
approved the first full budget of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) for 1998-99 here Wednesday, which is
described as a balanced plan in the time of economic uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
The budget, presented to the 60-seat Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) by Financial Secretary of the SAR government Donald
Tsang a month ago, was adopted by the legislature at its full
session Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers also approved two other bills -- the Merchant
Shipping (Registration) (Amendment) Bill 1998 and the Building
Management (Amendment) Bill 1998.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the legislators, Tsang said: "I am grateful to
the members of the PLC for welcoming the budget proposals and
responding generously to them in the debate."
</P>
<P>
Under the budget, the total expenditure for the new financial
year will amount to 248 billion HK dollars (32 billion
U.S. dollars) and the figure is equal to the government spending
of 233 billion HK dollars (30 billion U.S. dollars) plus 15.2
billion HK dollars (2 billion U.S. dollars) outlays from the
Capital Investment Fund.
</P>
<P>
The total revenue for 1998-99 is estimated at 247 billion HK
dollars (31.6 billion U.S. dollars). With 11.7 billion HK dollars
(1.5 billion U.S. dollars) worth of land fund added, the fiscal
reserves in the new financial year will stand at 10.7 billion HK
dollars (1.4 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The budget also plans a six-percent increase in duties on
tobacco, fuels and methyl alcohol.
</P>
<P>
"The surplus forecast for 1998-99 is prudent" and "the budget
is essentially a balanced one," the financial secretary said,
predicting a 3.5-percent growth in the SAR's Gross Domestic
Product in the new financial year, which starts from April 1, 1998
 and ends on March 31, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
