<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 18 (Xinhua) -- South Korea Wednesday urged Japan
to apologize for atrocities committed in World War II against
comfort women, or sex slaves, and to shoulder responsibility for
them.
</P>
<P>
"The Korean people will respect the Japanese if Japan
acknowledges the atrocities committed against comfort women,"
Foreign Affairs and Trade Minister Park Chung-soo said here in an
interview with Japanese media.
</P>
<P>
The comfort women were those who were forced to sexually serve
Japanese soldiers during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Japan should compensate these women, said Park Chug-soo.
</P>
<P>
In the past several months, South Koreans have frequently
demonstrated in front of the Japanese Embassy in Seoul, appealing
for an apology and compensation.
</P>
<P>
The total number of survivors from sex slavery registered in
eight countries stands at 22,280, according to the Korean Council
for the Women Drafted for Military Sexual Slavery, which got the
information from Japan's civic organization "ICR 98." 
