<HEADLINE> Karachi Stock Exchange Index Further Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Karachi Stock Exchange
(KSE) 100-Index dropped slightly Wednesday by 6.06 points to close
at 1520.26 against Tuesday's 1526.32.
</P>
<P>
A total of 70 million shares were traded on Wednesday against
65.05 million shares traded previous day.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the further dropping of KSE 100-Index was
in response to political uncertainty in Sindh Province with
brokers fearing that the main political party, Mutahhida qaumi
Movement (MQM), may break its alliance with the ruling Pakistan
Muslim League (N) in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
The MQM party has given a 48-hour ultimatum to the government
on Tuesday evening to solve the outstanding differences, otherwise
they would break away from their coalition alliance with the
ruling party.
</P>
<P>
Analysts warn that a break-up between the MQM and the ruling
party may affect Karachi's fragile law and order situation.
</P>
<P>
There are expectations that the stock market will continue its
slide on Thursday since there is little buying. Some brokers
predict, however, that the KSE 100-Index will go up a few points
in the week before leveling off at the 1600 level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
