<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Sees Need for Common Rules on Renewable Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, said there is a need for
a set of common rules on renewable sources of energy used to
generate electricity within a competition-based system.
</P>
<P>
A report on harmonization in the single electricity market,
adopted by the Commission, sets out some initial considerations on
questions arising from market support for renewable energy in
a liberalized internal electricity market, according to
European Report, a newsletter published in Brussels Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report, proposed by European Energy Commissioner Christos
Papoutsis, focused on environmental issues. It will now be
sent on to the EU's energy ministers for review.
</P>
<P>
The report, regarded as the first step towards a proposal for
an EU directive on this topic, emphasizes the Commission's view
that there is a need for common EU-wide rules on renewable sources
of energy such as solar, wave and wind power within a
competition-based system.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive body says that such a system will have clear
advantages in terms of cost effectiveness, trade and the quick
development of renewables. It will, in turn, result in the
strengthening of the technological leadership enjoyed by EU
industry in this field.
</P>
<P>
The report argues that renewables will need support because it
will continue to be generally more expensive to produce than
energy from conventional fuels.
</P>
<P>
The EU member states are now reportedly designing their own
schemes for the support of renewables, to include tax breaks,
levies, "green" licences and guaranteed prices as well as
assessments of the compatibility of these schemes with EU law.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to make rapid progress in this area. Renewable
energies represent a cornerstone in the Union's strategy for
reaching the Kyoto targets," said Mr. Papoutsis.
</P>
<P>
He also said that renewable sources of energy would promote job
creation in a "promising sector" and maintain the EU's leadership
in this field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Donates $5m to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Britain donated 3.1 million
Pound (some 5.1 million U.S. Dollars) to Uganda through the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), The Monitor reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Michael Cook, the British High Commissioner to Uganda,
revealed Tuesday the fund is to be used for UNICEF immunization
activities in the country.
</P>
<P>
The fund will help UNICEF and Ugandan Health Ministry to
implement fully and consolidate the nationwide expanded program
of immunization against the most common childhood diseases and
for the eradication of polio, the diplomat added.
</P>
<P>
The money is to be used to buy vaccines, immunization supplies
and clinical equipment, oral rehydration sachets plus
administrative costs, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Britain provided Uganda with 500,000 Pounds in 1995/1996 and
780,000 Pounds in 1996/1997 for immunization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
