<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia to Supply More Electricity to Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The supply of electric power from
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region to Beijing is expected to rise
considerably, so that power shortage in the Chinese capital will
be eased and the quality of its environment improved.
</P>
<P>
The capacity of power transmission to Beijing will reach two
million kw by the year 2000 on the current basis of 900,000 kw,
according to Liu Mingzu, chairman of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Regional Government, who is currently attending the annual session
of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
While working out its program for trans-century development,
Liu noted, Inner Mongolia has decided to turn its advantage in
coal resources into an economic edge.
</P>
<P>
The West Power Grid of Inner Mongolia, within the easy reach of
Beijing, is designed to have a generating capacity of 3.28 million
kw, and the capacity will reach 6.54 million kw by 2000.
</P>
<P>
After coping with local demands, more than three million kw
will be transferred to power grids in north China, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
When Beijing residents suffered rare, sustained hot summer
weathers last year, the Beijing-Tianjin-Tangshan Power Grid of the
North China Power Administration cut its power supply to some
other places in an effort to help guarantee the adequate supply of
electricity in the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
