<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Financial Institutions Expected to Enter S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Foreign financial institutions are
expected to enter South Korea in the second half of this year to
buy local banks, a South Korean organization said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Local banks will be primary targets of foreign financial
institutions when conditions for business operation are ripe, the
Samsung Economic Research Institute said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The report listed Seoul Bank and Korea First Bank as the top
targets, which are under preparation for sale, as are other small
ailing banks.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that all listed banks can easily recover normal
operations by improving management and rationalizing financial
operations, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
12 commercial banks have been closed while another 23 will be
examined subject to stringent rehabilitation criteria set by the
government.
</P>
<P>
Under the criteria, the 23 banks will have to raise their
capital adequacy ratio to more than four percent by the end of
this month, six percent by July and eight percent by June 1999.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks, which fail to meet the criteria, will either
be closed or forced to merge.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once an exuberant economic powerhouse in the
world, has been plagued by the economic crisis since late last
year and needs foreign capital to revitalize its economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
