<HEADLINE> Gates: Microsoft Investment Unaffected by Asian Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer Bill Gates said here Wednesday that his
company's investments in the region will not be affected by the
economic turmoil as they are long-term in nature.
</P>
<P>
"We do everything on a long-term basis and the investments we
are making in the region are not changed by the turmoil and
economic crisis," he told a press conference after meeting
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
Gates, who is on a one-day visit here as part of a regional
trip which also covers Australia, Singapore and the Philippines,
also had "very productive" meetings with other Malaysian cabinet
members and Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
He said issues discussed in the meetings included opportunities
for Microsoft in Malaysia, development of Malaysia's Multimedia
Super Corridor (MSC), education and the world market.
</P>
<P>
Gates expressed Microsoft's commitment to expanding the staff
strength of its operation in Malaysia, where the company has its
regional headquarters.
</P>
<P>
On Microsoft's participation in the MSC project, Gates, who is
the MSC's international advisory panel member, said: "I am a big
supporter of the basic concept driving the infrastructure."
</P>
<P>
The MSC, a 750 square kilometer zone located south of Kuala
Lumpur, is designated as the hub for development of multimedia
products and services in the country.
</P>
<P>
Gates said his visit here is meant to identify the roles
Microsoft can play in the MSC and his company is committed to
increasing the amount of things it does in the project.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Microsoft said in a statement that the company would
invest close to 1 million ringgit (about 272,479 U.S. dollars) in
developing and nurturing young Malaysian software programming
talent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
