<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Refugees in Netherlands to Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government set up a
special office Wednesday to help the country's over 300 refugees
in the Netherlands return home.
</P>
<P>
The refugees fled to Holland at the end of 1992 when the civil
war broke out again. However, their request for refuge was denied
by the Dutch government.
</P>
<P>
After bilateral consultations, the two governments signed a
cooperation deal in September 1997, which prescribes the
establishment of the refugee assistance office.
</P>
<P>
The office, under the agreement, is aimed at enhancing the
voluntary return of Angolan refugees, which will start from May
this year, with the Angolan government providing legal documents
necessary for their return, and the Dutch side offering financial
assistance.
</P>
<P>
The office will also help build facilities for the settlement
of the refugees and their employment, to ensure a secured living.
The returnees will have access to applying for bank loans to be
self-employed or join other collective ventures.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations statistics show that a total of three
million Angolans were reduced to refugees during the
two-decade-long civil war, 700,000 of which are staying in
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Although a cease fire was announced in 1994, the national
economy has been seriously damaged, which still poses difficulty
for the return of refugees from abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Archaeological Team Excavating Imperial Palace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Japanese team of
archaeologists will uncover the secrets of the rear palace, where
imperial concubines lived during the Western Han Dynasty (206
BC-24 AD), in the Guigong Palace Complex on the southern part of
the Western Han capital, in Chang'an.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Social Sciences' Institute of
Archaeology and the Nara National Cultural Properties Research
Institute announced today that they have begun the excavation work.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that the palace complex, which was
built by the Han emperor, Wudi, was famous for its architecture
and treasures. One of the buildings, the Mingguang Hall, was
decorated with gold, jade, and pearls that gave it a brightness at
night.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists have so far unearthed the foundation of a
2,700-sq.m. hall.
</P>
<P>
The Chang'an site is located to the northwest of the city of
Xi'an, the capital of Shaanxi Province, on 36 sq.km. of ground, an
area that is 50 times the size of Beijing's Forbidden City, where
the emperors of the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911)
dynasties lived.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists have been working on the city site since
the 1950s and have covered part of the city gates, the imperial
ancestral temple, central government buildings, and workshops.
</P>
<P>
In 1987, in government building remains they found more than
50,000 inscribed bone slips that are considered central government
archives.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists say that Chang'an was very nearly square and
had 12 gates, each of which had three portals allowing four carts
to pass at the same time.
</P>
<P>
An advanced water supply and drainage system was found in the
city which had well-planned streets, the longest of which
stretched for 5,500 m.
</P>
<P>
The imperial palaces were located in the southern part of the
city and include the Weiyang, Changle, Guigong, Beigong, and
Mingguang complexes.
</P>
<P>
Scholars say that the emperors lived in the Weiyang, their
mothers lived in the Changle, and their concubines in the other
three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Election of New Leadership Historic Event, Says Tung Chee Hwa </HEADLINE>
