<HEADLINE> Highlights of BJP National Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
the National Agenda released Wednesday by Atal Behari Vajpayee,
Indian prime minister-designate who will take oath Thursday:
</P>
<P>
-- To set up a commission to review the constitution in light
of the past 50 years of experience.
</P>
<P>
-- To re-evaluate the country's nuclear policy and exercise the
option to induct nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
-- To enact a Lok Pal (People's Supervisory Commission) bill
with adequate powers to deal with corruption charges against any
one including the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
-- To reserve 33 percent of seats for women in the parliament
and state assembles.
</P>
<P>
-- To give full statehood to Delhi and create new states like
Uttaranchal, Vananchal and Chattisgarh.
</P>
<P>
-- To undertake necessary electoral reforms.
</P>
<P>
-- To set up a national judicial commission to recommend
judicial appointments in high courts and the supreme court and to
draw up a code of ethics for the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
-- To establish a national security council to analyze the
military, economic and political threats to the nation and to
undertake India's first strategic defense review.
</P>
<P>
-- To give legal protection to the existing percentage of
reservation in educational institutions for minorities and
low-caste people at the state level.
</P>
<P>
-- To improve the Prasar Bharti Act on media and to enact a
broadcasting bill to regulate private broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
-- To restrict foreign equity holding in private television
broadcasting company to 20 percent and prevent cross-holding to
avoid emergence of monopolies in the media.
</P>
<P>
-- To seek national consensus on all major issues confronting
the nation by involving opposition parties and all sections of the
society.
</P>
<P>
-- To ensure equal pay for equal work for men and women.
</P>
<P>
-- To provide drinking water to all villages in the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
-- To eradicate illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
-- To make primary education free and compulsory up to the
fifth standard.
</P>
<P>
-- To evolve a national housing and habitat policy and build 2
million housing units annually.
</P>
<P>
-- To give free education to girls up to college level,
including professional courses.
</P>
<P>
-- To set up a development bank for women entrepreneurs in
small-scale and tiny sectors.
</P>
<P>
-- To draw a national charter for children.
</P>
<P>
-- To give incentives and disincentives for population control.
</P>
<P>
-- To set up a backward area commission to identify least
developed areas.
</P>
<P>
-- To set up a committee to study the feasibility of treating
all 19 ethnic languages listed in the constitution as official
languages.
</P>
<P>
-- To take steps to ensure harmonious center-state relations.
</P>
<P>
-- To draw up a national charter for social justice based on
the principle of social harmony.
</P>
<P>
-- To unveil a national environment policy to balance between
development and ecology.
</P>
<P>
-- To unveil a national informatics policy with short-, medium-
and long-term perspectives.  
</P>
</TEXT>
