<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Official on Nomination for EC Sub-sector Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Preparations for Hong Kong's
Election Committee (EC) sub-sector elections on April 2 have
reached the final stage as the nomination period is about to
conclude in two days.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference to review the progress of the
preparations, Justice Woo Kwok-hing, chairman of the Electoral
Affairs Commission, said that the whole situation of the
nomination is good, saying that so far a total of 436 nominations
have been received by the Hong Kong Registration and Electoral
Office since the nomination began on March 13.
</P>
<P>
He called on candidates intending to join the race to hand in
nomination forms without delay.
</P>
<P>
A total of 683 members of the Election Committee will be
returned from 35 sub-sector representing various trades,
profession, labor, social services, Chinese people's Political
Consultative Conference Hong Kong delegates and district-based
organizations.
</P>
<P>
These members, together with the 77 ex-officio members and 40
representatives nominated by the religious sub-sector, will form a
800-strong Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
Woo said a candidate who must be aged 18 or above and is a
registered elector for a geographical constituency only needs to
have his nomination paper subscribed by at least five voters
registered for the sub-sector concerned and pays an election
deposit of 1,000 HK dollars (128 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
If the number of candidates in a sub-sector is small than that
of members to be elected, there is no need to have elections in
that sub-sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
Woo said: "I hope to see as many candidates as possible from
various sub-sector come forward to give the 140,000 voters a
choice on April 2."
</P>
<P>
After the nomination period ends on March 20, he said
returning officers will draw lots to determine the order of names
of candidates on ballot papers and to allocate designated spots to
candidates for putting up election advertisements.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of arrangements on the polling day, Woo said that 96
polling stations had been identified and that polling would last
15 hours from morning till night.
</P>
<P>
The first Legislative Council of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region shall be composed of 60 members, with 20
returned by geographical constituencies through direct elections,
10 by the Election Committee and 30 by functional constituencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cyclists Eyes More Gold Medals in Bangkok Asiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese sports official said
here on Wednesday that the chief aim of the Chinese cyclists this
year is to win more gold medals at the 13th Asian Games scheduled
on December in Bangkok, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"This year's goal is to collect more gold medals in Bangkok
than those we won in Hiroshima Asiad in 1994," said Cai Jiadong,
president of the Chinese Cycling Association. "But in a long run,
we should seek a breakthrough in the 2000 Sydney Olympic Games."
</P>
<P>
Chinese cyclists claimed three gold medals, four silvers and
four bronzes but they have never won an Olympic medal in history.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17 gold medals will be awarded in the Bangkok Asian
Games and 18 golds on stake in Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"Generally speaking, our female cyclists enjoy an upper hand in
Asia. And several riders have had the calibre to win medals in
Olympics. But the male are still lagging far behind even in
Asia," Cai said.
</P>
<P>
Some 65 riders have gathered in the national training camp
since last December. They will take part in the trial competition
held later this year for qualifying for the Bangkok Asain Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
