<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM: Peace, Stability Key to Growth in South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Wednesday stressed the need for creating an environment of
peace and stability in South Asia for economic development and
regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We firmly believe that peace and security are key to the
economic development of the region," Sharif said while
inaugurating the Second Economic Cooperation Conference of the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) here
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference is attended by government officials and
delegates of chambers of commerce and industry of SAARC member
countries, which include Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said Pakistan is firmly committed to the ideal of a
friendly and cooperative South Asia engaged in mutually beneficial
economic activities.
</P>
<P>
"We are equally committed to the liberalization of trade in the
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The liberalization process has to be accompanied by parallel
efforts to remove non-tariff barriers and hidden subsidies that
impede and distort trade, deny a level playing field, undermine
mutuality of interest and prevent transparency, he said.
</P>
<P>
As long as these barriers plague the commercial environment,
the aims of the South Asian Preferential Trading Agreement (SAPTA)
and South Asian Free Trade Agreement (SAFTA) cannot be realized,
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Compared with other regions of the world, Sharif noted, "our
region is lagging behind in economic development."
</P>
<P>
Trading activity, a good indicator of economic dynamism, is
sadly not keeping pace with global trends, he said.
</P>
<P>
Representing one-fifth of the world population, he said, SAARC
member states have a dismal 1 percent share of the global trade.
Even the intra-regional trade is as low as 3 percent of the total
trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an estimated half billion people in South Asia are
still living in poverty with income and consumption levels below
nationally defined poverty lines and hunger, malnutrition and
illiteracy are rampant, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the government and private enterprises have to
work together to face these challenges.
</P>
<P>
"We need to universalize prosperity and eradicate poverty. What
is needed is a strong and mutual trust between the government and
business in order to put society on the path of sustainable
economic development," Sharif said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
