<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Legislators Approve Budget for 1998-99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Provisional legislators today
approved the first full budget of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) for 1998-1999, which is described as
a balanced plan in the time of economic uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
The budget, presented to the 60-seat Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) by Financial Secretary of the SAR government Donald
Tsang a month ago, was adopted by the legislature at its full
session Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Under the budget, the total expenditure for the new financial
year will amount to 248 billion HK dollars (32 billion U.S.
dollars) and the figure is equal to the government spending of 233
billion HK dollars (30 billion U.S. dollars) plus 15.2 billion HK
dollars (2 billion U.S. dollars) outlays from the Capital
Investment Fund.
</P>
<P>
The total revenue for 1998-1999 is estimated at 247 billion HK
dollars (31.6 billion U.S. dollars). With 11.7 billion HK dollars
(1.5 billion U.S. dollars) worth of land fund added, the fiscal
reserves in the new financial year will stand at 10.7 billion HK
dollars (1.4 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Noting that the lawmakers had not made any change to the budget
in the past month, Tsang reiterated: "The surplus forecast for
1998-1999 is prudent" and "the budget is essentially a balanced
one."
</P>
<P>
He also said that the SAR government has adhered to its prudent
fiscal policy and has observed the relevant provision of the Basic
Law.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law stipulates that the SAR shall follow the
principle of keeping expenditure within the limits of revenues in
drawing up its budget, and strive to achieve a fiscal balance,
avoid deficit and keep the budget commensurate with the growth
rate of its gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The new financial year starts from April 1, 1998 and ends on
March 31, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
