<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Arrives for Talks on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. chief's top envoy for
Cyprus arrived here early Wednesday for a six-day visit in a bid
to bring the leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities
back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his arrival, U.N. Secretary-General's Special
Advisor for Cyprus, Diego Cordovez said the U.N. is seriously
concerned about the situation in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He warned that international interest could wane if rival
sides on the island do not show political will for a settlement.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez's visit follows a Security Council decision last week
calling upon "both parties to take the practical steps necessary
to move the negotiating process forward in an effective manner."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council expressed concern over the "high
level of tension" in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez told reporters that outsiders are more interested in
solving the long-standing Cyprus problem than the Cypriots
themselves.
</P>
<P>
"It seems we are more interested, we the outsiders. The two
community leaders are the ones that have the responsibility to
work out a settlement, We can help them," Cordovez said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "the international community is extremely
concerned, but you know, there may be a moment when they may
simply give up and that would be tragic. I am trying to avoid
that."
</P>
<P>
Cordovez, the former Ecuadorean Foreign Minister, is expected
to have separate meetings with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash and Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides during his
visit. He will also have a meeting with the ambassadors of the
U.N. Security Council's five permanent members in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez's visit came at a time when the bicommunal peace
talks were in deadlock after the two rounds of U.N.-led direct
talks between the two Cypriot communities' leaders in the U.S. and
Switzerland last summer.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has stated that the Turkish Cypriots will not
participate in peace talks unless his breakaway state unilaterally
declared in northern Cyprus is recognized.
</P>
<P>
Denktash's position was taken after the European Union decided
to start accession talks with the Cypriot government scheduled on
March 31.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and took over the northern third of the island following a failed
pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus, which was only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez will leave on Sunday for Athens and end his trip
in the region with a visit to Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Exports to U.S. Up, Imports Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- South African exports to
the United States climbed steadily during the past year while
U.S. sales to South Africa fell, The Star daily Wednesday quoted
U.S. Department of Commerce as saying.
</P>
<P>
South African exports to the U.S. totaled 2.5 billion Dollars
last year, up eight percent from 1996. Imports of U.S. goods fell
three percent to three billion Dollars, reducing the trade
deficit for 1997 by more than a third from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Most of South African exports to the U.S. came from the sale
of platinum sponge valued at 564 million Dollars. U.S. imports
of South African iron and steel dropped by nine percent, or 31
million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Top of South Africa's U.S. import list are machinery,
including agricultural equipment, power generators and general
industrial machinery.
</P>
<P>
There is also roaring trade in aircraft and automobile parts,
tractors and engines, electrical and hi-tech equipment, including
office machines, computers and software, medical and
telecommunications parts.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's leading exports to the U.S. are metals, iron,
steel, metalliferous ores and non-metallic mineral manufactures.
Exports of inorganic chemicals are increasing at steady pace.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and Nigeria are the leading U.S. export markets
in sub-Saharan Africa, together they account for about 63 percent
of U.S. exports to the region.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, Angola, South Africa and Gabon are the leading import
suppliers. They accounted for 84 percent of U.S. imports from
sub-Saharan Africa last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
