<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Close Broadly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange closed broadly higher on Wednesday on a
moderately higher volume, reversing the weak trend in the last two
trading days.
</P>
<P>
The 100-companies benchmark Composite Index gained 6.34 points
to 706.55, the all main board Emas Index added 1.84 points to
179.14, but the Industrial Index was down 12.69 points to
1,254.09. The second board Index added 2.01 points to 180.20.
</P>
<P>
Gainers overwhelmed losers by 503 to 126 while 149 counters
were unchanged and 134 untraded.
</P>
<P>
Turnover increased to 199.519 million shares valued at 495.212
million ringgit (about 134.935 million U.S. dollars) from 142.135
million valued at 352.797 million ringgit (about 91.13 million
U.S. dollars) traded Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The main board turnover increased to 179.611 million shares
valued at 447.289 million ringgit (about 121.877 million U.S.
dollars) from 128.369 million valued at 320.022 million ringgit
(about 87.13 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second board's turnover rose to 19.908 million shares
valued at 47.923 million ringgit (about 13.058 million U.S.
dollars) from 13.766 million valued at 32.775 million ringgit
(about 8.93 million U.S. dollars) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Direct business deals fell to 3.920 million shares valued at
12.551 million ringgit (about 3.42 million U.S. dollars) from
Tuesday's 4.148 million shares valued at 21.399 million ringgit
(about 5.83 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Despite market ending higher Wednesday, the uncertainty is
still there and it remained to be seen where market would be
heading Thursday, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said at this stage, it is likely that the Composite
Index would stay range-bound between 720-690 as investors are
mostly holding on to their positions. 
</P>
