<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAR Official: HK Remains Attractive to Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's appealing to
international businesses remains despite the recent financial
problems in the region, Secretary for Justice Elsie Leung said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are still the world's freest and fairest market, with
minimum intervention by a clean government and clear rule of law,"
Leung said while officiating the opening ceremony of the Hong Kong
International Jewelry Show '98 here.
</P>
<P>
A 25 percent increase in the number of international traders
"shows that, nine months after the reunification, Hong Kong's
becoming a special administrative region of the People's Republic
of China has not affected its position as an international trade
and financial center and its participation in international
affairs continues freely and actively," she said.
</P>
<P>
The jewelry trade and industry has long been an important part
of Hong Kong's economy. As one of the largest exporters of
precious jewelry in the world, Hong Kong exported 10.5 billion HK
dollars (1.35 billion U.S. dollars) worth of jewelry products last
year.
</P>
<P>
The annual event moved this year into the new wing of the Hong
Kong Convention and Exhibition Center, site of the handover
ceremonies at the midnight of June 30 last year. This year's show
is expected to attract thousands of visitors worldwide, said Leung
Sik-wah, chairman of the Trade Development Council Jewelry
Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
More than 770 companies from 27 countries and regions are
participating in the four-day fair.
</P>
<P>
To provide convenience for both exhibitors and buyers, products
have been classified into 16 categories and a computerized
exhibitor system has been installed to save time in locating any
company of interest.
</P>
<P>
The event is organized by the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council in cooperation with the Hong Kong Jewelers' and
Goldsmiths' Association, the Hong Kong Jewelry and Jade
Manufacturers Association, the Hong Kong Jewelry Manufacturers'
Association and the Diamond Importers Association.  
</P>
</TEXT>
