<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Rise on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to rise
on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index (STII) gained 24.04 points to close at 1645.3 points on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that stock prices ended higher amid moderate fund
buying, with property stocks extending their recent rise.
</P>
<P>
They said that expectations that the property market may be
near its bottom and stabilizing interest rates have propelled
property stocks higher.
</P>
<P>
However, they noted that buying was cautious as players
continued to watch the socio-political and economic developments
in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume shrank to 287.44 million units, valued
at 419.37 million Singapore dollars (about 260.48 million U.S.
dollars). Advances overwhelmed declined by 280 to 75, while 256
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Hersing was the most actively traded stock as it registered a
turnover of 2.426 million units. It was followed by IPC
Corporation which had 15.42 million shares traded. DBS
(Development Bank of Singapore) Land was next with 13 million
shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS Foreign led the gainers of the day as it rose by 50 cents
to finish at 13.1 Singapore dollars. Local car distributor Cycle &AMP;
Carriage (C&AMP;C) increased by 45 cents to end at 7.15 Singapore
dollars, while Bukit Sembawang gained 35 cents to close at 9.85
Singapore dollar.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the biggest loser as it
declined by 1.3 dollars to end at 35.3 Singapore dollars. Cerebos
fell by 22 cents to close at 4.14 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
