<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT 10:00, March 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- The Romanian government on Tuesday adopted a draft
budget for fiscal 1998 that promises to rein in the country's
runaway hyper-inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian news agency said that under the budget, the
government will keep inflation rate under 45 percent, budget
deficit under 3.6 percent of the nation's Gross Domestic Product
(GDP), and try to achieve a zero economic growth. (Romania-Budget)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- A high-tech brain-drain has cost Yugoslavia three
billion U.S. dollars during the international embargo, the
development minister said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 scientists specializing in high-technology flew
out of Yugoslavia between 1991 and 1996 when the embargo was
implemented against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, said Jagos
Zelenovic, Minister of Development, Science and
Environment. (Yugoslavia-Brain Drain)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Prince Norodom Ranariddh was sentenced in his
absence to 30 years in prison Wednesday for conspiring to
overthrow the coalition government with the help of Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
It is the second trial of the deposed first prime minister in
his absence. On March 4, he was convicted of illegally buying and
transporting weapons and sentenced to five years in
prison. (Cambodia-Ranariddh-Sentence)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukraine insists on demarcating the Ukraine-Russia
borders in the Black Sea, the Azov Sea and the Kerich Strait in
line with international laws, a Ukrainian official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Anto Buterko, first Deputy Foreign Minister of Ukraine, said
his country believed it was necessary to determine related
countries' boundaries in these areas according to international
laws.(Ukraine-Russia-Black Sea)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Kosovo is an internal affair of Yugoslavia,
President Slobodan Milosevic claimed again Tuesday, when he met
with visiting Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported that Milosevic said
the Kosovo issue could only be solved by political means within
Serbia.(Yugoslavia-Russia-Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
