<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Records Growth in January Textile Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China exported textiles and
clothing valued at over three billion US dollars during January,
up 9.18 percent on last year's same month, according to today's
International Business Daily.
</P>
<P>
The nation recently introduced a series of measures to boost
textile exports and cut production costs. The steps were
taken to increase exports which declined somewhat in the last
quarter of 1997 due to the financial crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
January textile exports to the United States surged by 49
percent, those to Germany up by 25 percent and those to Russia by
85 percent on the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
However, the effects of the prevailing financial turmoil
lingered with exports to Hong Kong dropping by 12 percent, Japan
by 11 percent, and the Republic of Korea by 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
The daily stressed that China should make full use of its
products with a high added value and brand names in order to gain
a greater share of the international textile and clothing markets.
</P>
<P>
The daily predicted that China's textile exports will witness
consistent growth this year in spite of increasingly fierce
competition and the ongoing financial crisis in Southeast
Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
