<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed slightly higher Wednesday after a strong performance by
bank and insurance stocks, fueled by a strong bond market.
</P>
<P>
But the bourse lost its earlier momentum in afternoon trade,
retreating from its highs after falls on Asian stock markets.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries closed just 2.5 points higher at 2769.6,
despite an overnight record high on Wall Street and a strong start
to the day that included an intra-day high of 2789.4.
</P>
<P>
The intra-day record for the index was 2797.3 set on September
25 last year.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones Broker Philip Toop said some re-rating
in the insurance sector had most probably helped buoy its stocks,
which pushed the index up a massive 194.6 points, or 2.62 percent
to 7618.9.
</P>
<P>
Insurance stocks were popular with investors seeking higher
yield, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
They attributed the rise in insurance stocks to rallies in both
the bond and equities markets.
</P>
<P>
Insurance heavyweight National Mutual Holdings was behind the
index surge, edging up 9 cents to 3.45 Australian dollars, a move
of 2.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
Banks were also among the market leaders with the relevant
index up 37 points to 5722.8.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank shares were 22 cents stronger at 21.47
Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank rose by 11.6 cents to 18.16
Australian dollars, Westpac was up 2 cents at 10.6 Australian
dollars and ANZ increased 11 cents to 10.47 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index finished 11.9 points stronger at
4775.2, after peaking at 4806.2.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said leading stocks News Corp., BHP, Amcor and Telstra
all contributed to dragging the All Industrials down from its
earlier highs.
</P>
<P>
News Corp. was 7 cents weaker at 10.38 Australian dollars with
the preferred shares down 5.5 cents to 8.82 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 376.22 million shares worth 662.57
million U.S. dollars with falls of 613 outnumbering rises of 536.
</P>
<P>
The All Resources Index slipped 6.3 points to 1165.7, with
leading miner BHP down 15 cents at 15.68 Australian dollars,
holding the market back as investors took profits following strong
rises in the resources giant after Managing Director John Prescott
resigned recently, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto shares climbed 10 cents to 19.5 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was down 10 points to 1099.6 after the price of
gold fell from Tuesday's close of 294.15 U.S. dollars an ounce.
Gold bullion closed Wednesday at 292.1 U.S. dollars an ounce.
</P>
</TEXT>
