<HEADLINE> National Sanitation Week '98 Begins in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A "National Sanitation Week '98"
was inaugurated here and elsewhere in the country on Wednesday in
an effort to build up people's awareness of the importance of
proper sanitation for their health and the environment.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inaugural ceremony, Minister for Local
Government and Rural Development and Cooperative Zillur Rahman
said that the government was pledge-bound to improve the state of
child health in the country, and had taken a five-year sanitation
program at a cost of 1.45 billion taka (about 31.5 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The death of about 85,000 children each year from Diarrheal
diseases in the country could be avoided if their families could
use safe drinking water and adopt proper hygienic habits, he said.
</P>
<P>
Women should be integrated in all development endeavors
relating to safe drinking water and campaign on proper hygienic
habits among the people, he said, adding "Mothers pay the key role
in ensuring proper habits of the children and overall cleanliness
in the family."
</P>
<P>
He also called on the mass media to increase the coverage on
the sanitation campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
