<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior German Officials to Visit Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Two senior German Foreign
Ministry officials will visit Iran to mend Bonn-Tehran relations,
local daily newspaper Iran News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The trip will take place in April following the Iranian new
year (to start March 21) holidays," the daily quoted an
unidentified source, adding that the two German officials are
directors general of political and consular affairs of the German
Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first trip of senior German officials to Iran
after the warm-up of relations between Iran and the European Union
(EU), whose recalled ambassadors returned to Tehran last November.
</P>
<P>
The EU states withdrew their envoys to Tehran after a German
court accused Iranian leaders last April of sponsoring state
terrorism against Iranian Kurdish rebel leaders in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Observers believed that the two German officials decided to
travel to Iran with an aim to discuss an Iranian death sentence on
the German citizen Helmut Hofer who was imprisoned on charges of
having illegal sexual relations with an Iranian Muslim woman.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel warned last month that
the improvement of Bonn-Tehran relations would depend on Hofer's
fate, but Iranian officials dismissed the warning by saying
that the case was a judicial one and had nothing to do
with diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Hofer was arrested in Iran last September and was sentenced
to death for having sexual relations with an Iranian Muslim
woman. The Iranian laws ban sexual relations between a Muslim
woman and a non-Muslim man.
</P>
<P>
Hofer has appealed to Iran's higher court by claiming that
he had converted to Islam before having a case with the
Iranian woman. Iranian judicial authorities stated earlier that
the verdict on Hofer might be changed if his claim was
proved by necessary document. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
