<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Sends Message to Clinton to Deflect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 18 (Xinhua) -- To deflect further pressure,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has sent a message to
United States President Bill Clinton on advancing the peace
process, Israel Radio reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The radio said Netanyahu was trying to prevent the publication
of a new U.S. peace plan on breaking the stalemate in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process. No details of the message were
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's move came apparently following the diplomatic
uproar created by visiting British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook,
who exerted pressure on Israel to halt its settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
Cook, who visited Israel Tuesday in the capacity of the
rotating presidency of the European Union (EU), was currently on a
Mideast tour trying to help revive the peace process by supporting
the Palestinian demand for ending Israeli settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
The trip has taken him to Egypt, Jordan and Palestinian
self-rule areas, and will also take him to Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Despite Israel's angry protests, Cook visited the controversial
Har Homa site in Arab East Jerusalem, where Israel is building a
settlement. He also met with Palestinian Council members at the
site to hear their complaints.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who met with Cook for one hour Tuesday evening,
canceled a scheduled dinner with Cook in a rare diplomatic
snub. He reiterated that Israel would never relinquish its
sovereign claim over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Cook denounced Israeli settlement expansion for undermining the
peace process, saying that his Har Homa visit was aimed at telling
Israel that the international community has the legitimate right
to express its deep concern over the issue. The Har Homa
construction has been one of the major obstacles blocking
progress in the Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United Nations Assembly has issued a
condemnation of Israeli construction of the Har Homa
settlement. It also called for a conference of the parties to the
Geneva Conventions to discuss Israeli settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
But Israel believes that as long as it is supported by the
United States, its closest ally, it can resist any other outside
pressures, including those from the EU.
</P>
<P>
Since the Iraq-U.N. crisis over weapons inspection last month,
Washington has not yet refocused its attention on the deadlock in
the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, which have been stalled since
March 1997.
</P>
<P>
The disputes between the Palestinians and Israelis mainly focused
on two issues: Israel's continued efforts to expand settlements in
the territories, and Israel's refusal to carry out the delayed
further troop redeployment in the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
