<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar dropped
more than half a U.S. cent Wednesday in sympathy with its New
Zealand counterpart after the Reserve Bank of New Zealand eased
interest rates by twice the amount anticipated by financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed the local session at 66.53 U.S.
cents, from 66.93 cents in Sydney late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It had begun on a much stronger note at 67.15 U.S. cents but
was quickly knocked back when the New Zealand central bank eased
official rates by 150 basis points, instead of the expected 75.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Reserve Bank Governor Don Brash forecast
substantially weaker export growth in the coming year, saying the
central bank was easing monetary conditions to prevent a sharp
decline in the economy because of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank Chief Economist Craig James said the
Australian dollar and the New Zealand dollar "tend to be lumped
together by global fund managers."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 86.72 Japanese yen from 86.65
and at 1.2132 Deutsche marks from 1.2168.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
