<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Share Prices Plunge on Fading Hope for Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo on
Wednesday in the wake of a statement by a senior official of the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) that new economy-boosting
measures will not include income tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange sank 377.52 points or 2.22 percent
from Tuesday's close to 16,619.68.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all issues on the
First Section, dropped 16.68 points or 1.31 percent to 1,253.09.
</P>
<P>
First Section volume went up to an estimated 430 million shares
from Tuesday's 388.83 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries was Wednesday's most heavily traded
issue.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo stock market opened slightly higher on a media report
that the government will draw up additional economic stimulus
measures by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
In the mid-morning, stock market players, mainly foreign
investors, accelerated selling following the U.S. dollar's surge
to the 130 yen level for the first time in two months.
</P>
<P>
The yen selling was prompted by a comment by the LDP's top
policy-planner Taku Yamasaki, who hinted in a newspaper interview
that income tax cuts were not appropriate to shore up the economy.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,330 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outpaced winners 818 to 294 with 139 issues unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
