<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese President Ends State Visit to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese President Tran
Duc Luong left here Wednesday afternoon for Singapore after a
three-day state visit, the first by a Vietnamese head of state
since the two countries established diplomatic ties in 1973.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese president's state visit, aimed at enhancing
bilateral ties between the two Southeast Asian nations, was also
to reciprocate the visit by Tuanku Ja'afar to Vietnam in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia paid tribute to the Vietnamese leader's visit as
Malaysia was chosen as the first country to visit by the president
since he took office last September.
</P>
<P>
During the "historic" visit, Tran Duc Luong held bilateral
discussions with Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad on
bilateral, regional and international issues such as the economic
crisis faced by Malaysia and other ASEAN countries, the
forthcoming ASEAN summit, the Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) and the
Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has agreed to the promotion of intra-ASEAN trade using
their own currencies.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Vietnam reaffirmed its policy to develop
friendship, good neighborliness and multi-faceted cooperation with
Malaysia on the basis of respect for independence, sovereignty and
non-interference in each other's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Tran Duc Luong said at a state banquet hosted by Malaysian King
Tuanku Ja'afar in his honor that over the years Vietnam and
Malaysia had observed fine development in friendship and
multi-faceted cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that since economic cooperation was becoming a
primarily important area in intra-ASEAN cooperation, especially in
view of the regional financial and currency crisis, Vietnam and
Malaysia needed to step up the areas of cooperation tantamount to
the existing fine political cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said within the framework of the ASEAN market and
international market, the two countries still have great
potentials which can be explored further so as to make full use of
each country's advantages.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Malaysia pledged to assist Vietnam in
drawing up the individual action plan required by the APEC and
also to help Vietnam with the preparation of the Common Effective
Preferential Tariff (CEPT) list that is required by the ASEAN Free
Trade Area (AFTA) scheme.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam became a member of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) in 1995 and is expected to be admitted into APEC
along with Peru and Russia during the informal meeting of the APEC
leaders to be held here in November.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam will host the ASEAN Summit in December.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia expressed its satisfaction with Vietnam's active role
in international affairs since its entry into ASEAN in 1995 and
welcomed measures introduced by the Vietnamese government to
promote intra-ASEAN trade.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and Vietnam have concluded many agreements in the
fields of economic, trade, investment, scientific and
technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is the seventh largest investor in Vietnam. As of
December 31, 1997, Vietnam approved 64 Malaysian projects with a
total capital outlay of 1.35 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Total trade between Malaysia and Vietnam in 1997 stood at 1.356
billion ringgit (358.73 million U.S. dollars) compared with 1.191
billion ringgit (315.08 million U.S. dollars) in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
