<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Americans Sue Boeing Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Forty-one ethnic American
workers sued the world largest aircraft maker Boeing company
Tuesday, seeking more than 82 million dollars for alleged racial
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit accuses the aerospace giant of failing to promote
ethnic workers, creating a hostile work environment,
discriminatory hiring practices and sexual harassment, according
to a report reaching here from Seattle, where the company is
located.
</P>
<P>
Among the plaintiffs, the report said, forty are Afro-Americans
and one is Filipino-American. All are current or former Being
employees.
</P>
<P>
They said that many of them were denied promotions granted to
others with equal or lesser qualifications, or offered promotions
that required them to transfer when others were not required to do
so.
</P>
<P>
Jim Dagnon, senior vice president of the company, promised that
his company would investigate the allegations and "appropriately
address" the problem, if any. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
