<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian PM-Designate Releases National Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- India's new government would
adopt a "consensual mode of governance", eradicate unemployment
and reevaluate the country's unclear policy, Prime
Minister-designate Atal Bihari Vajpayee declared here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will strive to develop national consensus on all major
issues confronting the nation by involving opposition parties and
all sections of the society in dialogue," said Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference following his release of the
eight-page national agenda on the eve of assuming office that he
would try for a consensual mode of governance as far as
practicable.
</P>
<P>
The new government led by the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)
would establish a national security council which would undertake
India's first ever strategic defense review, said Vajpayee, who
will resume office as India's 12th prime minister Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We will reevaluate the nuclear policy and exercise the option
to induct nuclear weapons," the agenda said. "We are committed to
ensuring safety and security of all citizens in all parts of the
country."
</P>
<P>
On international relations, the agenda said, the BJP government
would "reorient" the country's diplomacy to pursue economic and
commercial goals and strengthen regional and civilizational
groupings.
</P>
<P>
Asserting that it would pursue "genuine secularism", it said
"we will truly uphold and practice the concept of secularism
consistent with the Indian tradition" of equal respect for all
faiths and on the basis of equality of all.
</P>
<P>
Outlining its economic policy of the BJP government, the
national agenda said it would give a strong self-reliance thrust
to the reform process to move on to a seven percent growth bracket
with an ultimate goal to eradicate unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The document proposed to set up a committee to study
feasibility of treating all 19 languages included in the
Constitution as "official language".
</P>
<P>
A national judicial commission would be set up to recommend
judicial appointments in high courts and supreme courts and draw
up a code of ethics for the judiciary, said the agenda.
</P>
<P>
To deal with corruption, the agenda said, the BJP-led
government would enact a bill with adequate powers to deal with
corruption charges against anyone, including the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The agenda was signed by 17 persons, all leaders of the BJP and
its allies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
