<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Consumer Prices Increase by 3.9 percent in February  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's consumer
prices increased by 3.9 percent in February as compared with
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) shows that the food prices rose
by 17.4 percent mainly due to increased prices of rice, maize
flour, beef, fish, cooking oil, beans and cowpeas while prices of
drinks and tobacco increased by 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The monthly report says the prices of clothes and footwear
rose by 3.4 percent, transportation rates up by 10 percent and
the educations fees up by 7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The resport indicates that the prices of furniture and
household equipment like cookers, sewing machines, utensils,
torch batteries, laundry soap, insecticdes, bicycle tyres as well
as car service charges all increased to different extent.
</P>
<P>
The CPI covers prices collected in 20 main urban centers. The
prices cover 212 items and are the prevailing market prices.
</P>
<P>
The recent El Nino rains, which have paralized the transport
network in many parts of Tanzania and reduced crop production, is
partly blamed for a sharp rising of consumer goods prices, the
report adds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
