<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal, Bangladesh to Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Nepal and Bangladesh agreed to
expand the scope of their cooperation and increase bilateral trade
at a Joint Economic Commission meeting attended by their finance
ministers, press reports here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day meeting which ended Tuesday, the finance
ministers of the two countries also agreed to encourage
joint-venture investment.
</P>
<P>
The areas of bilateral cooperation agreed upon include industry
and investment, trade and commerce, water resources, education,
health, communication, tourism and civil aviation, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Bangladeshi Finance Minister Shah Kibria and his
Nepalese counterpart Rabindra Nath Sharma also discussed the
possibility of Nepal importing natural gas from Bangladesh and
exporting hydropower to that country.
</P>
<P>
The joint commission was established in January 1978 with the
objective of promoting economic cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Kibria said Bangladesh is working to upgrade the physical
infrastructure of the Phulbari transit route to make it
economically viable in the near future so as to boost trade
between Bangladesh and Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The transit route runs from Kakarbhitta of Nepal to the
Bangladeshi border town of Banglabandh through Phulbari in
northeastern India and then to the Mongla port in southwestern
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Except on the inauguration day last September, the route
remains idle due to impractical operating modalities and lack of
infrastructure in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The commerce secretaries of Nepal and India will meet in New
Delhi later this month to review the operating modalities.
</P>
<P>
"Nepal appreciated the positive gesture shown by Bangladesh to
further facilitate the export of Nepalese primary products to
Bangladesh and to consider Nepalese request for customs tariff
reduction," Nepal's Sharma was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the last fiscal year which ended on July 14, 1997, Nepal's
exports to Bangladesh amounted to about 357 million Nepali rupees
(about 5.7 million U.S. dollars) and imports stood at some 680
million rupees (about 11 million dollars), reports said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal and Bangladesh are both members of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) and members of the
so-called Growth Quadrangle, a sub-regional cooperation grouping
within the SAARC.
</P>
<P>
The Growth Quadrangle which also groups Bhutan and India was
initiated in December 1996 to develop jointly the eastern
Himalayan rivers for rapid economic development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
