<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Rebuffs U.S. Stance on Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
rebuffed the statement of the United States that it would not
accept a military candidate in Nigeria's presidential elections
this year, saying it amounts to undue interference in Nigeria's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Information and Culture Minister Chief Ikeabasi Mokelu, in a
press statement issued in the capital Abuja Tuesday, said
Nigerians are free to elect whomever they want, without America
imposing its will.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs Susan
Rice said last Thursday that any military candidate or top
government official who emerges as civilian president in Nigeria
would not be accepted by her government.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. position is a "negation of the basic principle of
democracy and civilized behavior", said Mokelu.
</P>
<P>
"And if our people choose to vote for a military candidate
later this year, no nation on earth, no matter how powerful or
wealthy, can usurp their sovereign right to elect whomsoever they
wish to become their president," he said.
</P>
<P>
He accused the United States of trying to foist its own
culture and political practices on other nations in the guise of
safeguarding democracy and human rights.
</P>
<P>
Under the Nigerian military government's transition to civil
rule program, presidential elections are billed to start in
August and the civilian president will take over power from the
military on October 1.
</P>
<P>
So far only two political figures have announced their
intention to contest, while many people are waiting for the
decision of the Head of State, General Sani Abacha, who is said
to make known his position on the issue in a few weeks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
