<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployed Farmers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li Shuqing, head of the Institute of Sociology of Hebei
Province's Social Science Academy, says that, as more transient
workers return to their villages with capital, technology and
information, it will bring economic change to rural parts of China.
</P>
<P>
According to some reports, 300,000 transient workers from
Sichuan Province in southwest China have returned home to start
businesses, and tens of thousands of farmers from Hunan, Hubei,
Anhui, Guizhou and Henan provinces have returned home to make
their fortune. More than 60 percent of the owners of 2.4 million
private businesses in Hebei have worked for some time in urban
factories.
</P>
<P>
About 80 million Chinese farmers have been trained by work they
found on their own, involving not a penny of government funds,
according to Li Yining, a professor of economics at Beijing
University.
</P>
<P>
This is a major investment in human resources, he says, and if
only a third or a quarter of the rural workers return home, great
changes will take place in their home towns.
</P>
<P>
This prediction is becoming a reality in China's rural areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
