<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Tries to Meet EU's Fish Imports Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan Health Ministry will
send officials to tour the country's fishing processing plants to
see whether they have implemented the hygiene standards demanded
by the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking Tuesday after receiving Lutz Salzmann, Head of the
Nairobi Mission of the delegation of the European Commission,
Kenyan Health Minister Jackson Kalweo said Kenya was seriously
addressing the issue of the ban on Kenya's fish exports by EU,
the Kenya Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In January, an EU committee meeting in Brussels decided to ban
import of fresh fish from four African countries including Kenya
because of cholera outbreak in the east African region.
</P>
<P>
"Cholera is still in the region and the ban will continue
until the disease is brought under control," said Lutz Salzmann.
</P>
<P>
"It is very important that the country (Kenya) implements the
general hygiene standards on fish processing by the June 30
deadline or risk being totally shut out from the European
markets," the EU official warned.
</P>
<P>
Salzmann expressed the hope that a new inspection team from EU
will come to Kenya to review the situation of fish processing in
the country and give necessary recommendations before the
deadline.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Fish exports to the European markets can earn the
country 10 million U.S. Dollars a year. But now, the fishing
industry is being seriously affected by the EU ban.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
