<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Commercialization Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Deputies from both water-abundant
southern provinces and arid northern areas to the National
People's Congress (NPC), in session here since early March, have
shown great concern for the grave situation of water shortages in
China and called for making water a commodity.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, the Chinese cabinet, has promulgated a
number of regulations on efficient use of water resources and is
working on regulations imposing charges for the use of water
resources, according to Niu Maosheng, minister of water resources,
who is attending the annual NPC session as a deputy.
</P>
<P>
China is one of 13 most water-deficient countries in the world.
With a rapid growth in population and in the amount of water used,
there has been an acute imbalance of water supply and demand in
recent years. Water shortages constitute a major factor
restricting China's economic growth and social development, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, waste of water can be seen everywhere, especially
seriously in agriculture, whose water consumption accounts for 75
percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
Wang Guangping, a deputy from Anhui Province, a leading grain
producer in east China, said only 30 percent of water is
effectively used in Anhui because a traditional way of irrigation,
"flooding", is still widely used.
</P>
<P>
A farmer deputy from north China's Inner Mongolia, named Tian
Ying, said local farmers water a ha. of farmland with as much as
9,000 cubic meters of water. Actually two thirds can be saved with
such new methods as spraying and drop irrigation, she said.
</P>
<P>
A major cause for the drying-up of the Yellow River at its
lower section for much of the year was the excessive use of water
for irrigation in the upper and middle reaches of the river, said
Chen Xiaoguo, a deputy from the Yellow River Water Conservancy
Committee.
</P>
<P>
In addition, only half of water for industrial use has been
recycled. The consumption of water for every 10,000 yuan of
industrial output value in China averages 200 cubic meters, three
fourths more than that in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
In the past four decades, the government has invested 300
billion yuan in building 80,000 reservoirs across the country,
which have brought total irrigated area from 13.3 million ha to
46.6 million ha nationwide, accounting for 22 percent of the
world's total, Niu said.
</P>
<P>
However, the state has so far imposed no charge on the use of
water for agriculture and collects a limited fee for water in
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Deputies attending the NPC session urged the state to enact
laws and regulations on water use and commercialize water supply
to ensure that the country have adequate water supply in the 21st
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hyacinth to Cost E. Africa 150 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Environment degradation of Lake
Victoria is to impose east Africa a loss of 150 million U.S.
Dollars a year, if water hyacinth is not controled.
</P>
<P>
The warning was made by Aquatics Unlimited, an American
company in its February report which was quoted by local newspaer
the New Vision Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report urged governments in Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda to
make quick measures to curb water hyacinth, the main cause of
degradation of the lake.
</P>
<P>
The wed appeared in the lake in the 1950s and developed
rapidly in recent years. It consumes a large amount of oxygen in
water and thus exchanged the ecological balance of the marine
organism system in the lake and caused a dangerous threat to the
ecological environment in the lake. Besides, the wed always
blocks up the transport on the lake.  
</P>
</TEXT>
