<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployed Farmers (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to a survey by China Labor Journal, 13.3 percent of
China's unemployed rural workers have the idea of returning home
to start businesses.
</P>
<P>
The 300,000 people in Sichuan now employ 800,000 local
laborers. This "job seeking" economy is new in China, but has
caught the government's attention.
</P>
<P>
For the past two years, parts of Hebei have developd a strategy
for becoming a part of "Greater Beijing" and have asked local job
seekers to bring in capital, technology and projects from other
cities. Lixian County near Baoding city has gotten 80 million yuan
from outside in this way.
</P>
<P>
To get people to return home in an orderly way, Sichuan has
decided to establish a center for returning job seekers in Jintang
County to provide services.
</P>
<P>
More officials are interested in attracting overseas investment
and have started encouraging job seekers to return home.
</P>
<P>
"The change from job seeking to starting a business has helped
us understand that urban areas and economically-developed coastal
areas have not only offered jobs to several million surplus rural
laborers who send back billions of yuan in earnings, but have also
helped train a generation for future development in the vast rural
areas," says Li Shuqing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Attempts to Ensure Uninterrupted Flow of Yellow River (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Xinhua Writer Hu Lujie and Ding Yaqing
</P>
<P>
 Alternative Measures
</P>
<P>
China has introduced a number of alternative measures to
increase water resources in the Yellow River Valley. For example,
the Ministry of Water Resources has strengthened its unified
control of water usage to more institutions in the middle and
lower reaches of the Yellow River Valley.
</P>
<P>
In addition to planting more trees, introducing more vegetation
and controlling soil erosion in the upper reaches of the river,
northeast China has introduced a special plan to develop
underground water resources and raising the use rate of related
resources to the worldwide average of between 60-70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Northwest China's Qinghai Province recently announced it will
launch expanded large-scale cloud-seeding operation in the upper
reaches of the Yellow River Valley during 1998.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the Xiaolangdi Project, a major multi-purpose
project funded by the World Bank, is proceeding smoothly in the
middle reaches of the river valley in Henan Province. The massive
reservoir, scheduled for completion in 2001, will provide ample
water supplies during peak irrigation seasons.
</P>
<P>
Shandong Province will continue to allocate massive investments
to sink more wells and build additional reservoirs to ensure water
supplies in areas along the Yellow River, as well as for
introducing efficient irrigation facilities to an additional one
million hectares of cultivatable land.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in the 629-km section of the Yellow River in Shandong
Province have already sunk 240,000 wells to tap underground water
resources for both production and daily life activities.
</P>
<P>
Central government top leaders have exhibited great concern
about the extended periods of interrupted water flow along the
Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
During recent discussions with Henan deputies to Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC), both Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
former premier Li Peng, who is now Chairman of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC), called for
harnessing of the Yellow River at strategic points and for giving
priority on ensuring the rational use of water resources in the
Yellow River Valley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
