<HEADLINE> TAZARA to Launch Regional Marketing Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania-Zambia railway
authority (TAZARA) is to embark on a vigorous marketing campaign
to lure countries in the sub-region to engage the railway company
in the transportation of their import and export goods, the TAZARA
Managing Director said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Zambia Daily Mail, TAZARA Managing
Director Kingston Mkandawire said marketing expeditions are
underway to Malawi, the Democratic Republic of Congo, Botswana
and Zimbabwe to lure them to use the company's services.
</P>
<P>
"We wanted to improve on our services, first make them
reliable, then go out to sell so that our customers would not be
disappointed," Mkandawire said.
</P>
<P>
Transit times for the train have been reduced from 15-16
days in some cases previously to three days now. The result of
this achievement has been improved security for traffic on
TAZARA.
</P>
<P>
By adjusting the way the trains run, the company has
drastically reduced its fuel costs as well, which saves it
120,000 litres of diesel cost per week, said thE director.
</P>
<P>
"I see TAZARA becoming a good company and a reliable railway
line. We want to see a situation where people quit using South
Africa's Spoornet and road transport and come to TAZARA because
it is the company of the future," Mkandawire noted.
</P>
<P>
TAZARA recorded a 30 billion Kwacha (about 22 million U.S.
Dollars) profit from passenger and freight services in the first
half of the 1997-98 financial year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, its workers both in Tanzania and Zambia will from
July 1 be receiving their salaries pegged to the dollar at the
ruling rate in both countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
