<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer Lawmaker Performs His Duty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Duan Youlin, a farmer from
central China's Hunan Province, could hardly hold back his tears
as he made his way up a few long flights of steps to the Great
Hall of the People in Beijing for the first full session of
China's top legislature of a new term, the Ninth National People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
Though he has had rich life experiences and has been to many
places including the United States and Japan, it had never occurred
to him that he would be elected to the country's top legislature
and discuss state affairs with other deputies, many of them also
high-ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
But to some 4,000 folks back in his village, the 54-year-old
Duan is "somebody"-- during the 1960s and early 70s, he was
enthusiastically involved in "class struggles;" and then, years
later, with equal enthusiasm, he cashed in on economic reforms in
the 1980s by leading his villagers in setting up workshops,
launching industrial enterprises, doing wholesaling and retailing
and establishing trade firms.
</P>
<P>
"We used to rely heavily on the government for food and money
and did not really have our own ideas on political issues. But now
we are free to air our views on state affairs," said Duan, one of
the rags-to-riches Chinese whose personal properties are valued at
more than a million yuan (more than 100,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Duan said he does not feel embarrassed among the many
intellectuals and senior officials in his delegation of deputies
to the NPC, in session here since early March.
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, I take pride in my being a farmer deputy.
Like the other deputies, my rights are protected by law," Duan
said.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that he was ill at ease in the presence of
ministers and governors during the first few days in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"We take the same bus (to the meeting venue), eat in the same
dinning hall and discuss matters of common concern on an equal
footing, and we have become quite familiar with each other," he
said. "Now I am no longer ill at ease and say what I like."
</P>
<P>
Duan is devoted to his duties and responsibilities as a
people's representative. Before he came to Beijing, he had
consulted a former local NPC deputy on NPC-related matters,
including procedures to file proposals. He also visited 14
government departments of his county as well as many villages to
acquaint himself with local conditions.
</P>
<P>
"The threshold of my house was almost flattened with so many
visitors who wanted me to pass their opinions and suggestions to
higher officials," recalled Duan. "One farmer even walked four
kilometers on foot to talk to me in my home."
</P>
<P>
Duan had the first experience of exercising his power as an NPC
deputy in Changsha, capital of Hunan Province, where deputies from
all parts of the province gathered before leaving for Beijing as
the provincial delegation.
</P>
<P>
A woman found Duan and complainted to him that she had
exhausted herself by trying to get her lawsuit accepted because
local judicial departments for several years had shifted the
responsibility onto one other.
</P>
<P>
Duan discussed the matter with the city's mayor, also an NPC
deputy, who immediately gave orders to relevant departments to
handle the case at the earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
Having received an education equivalent to junior middle
school, Duan is very diligent and has been spending more time
expanding his knowledge.
</P>
<P>
He has bought a lot of books during the session time, many of
which are about laws. He is one of the initiators of two motions
and four written suggestions to the current NPC session.
</P>
<P>
"I hope I am a competent NPC deputy," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Road Infrastructure in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved a 450
million U.S. dollar loan on Tuesday to help finance Argentina's
National Highways Rehabilitation and Maintenance Project.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to rehabilitate 7,844 kliometers of
roads or 40 percent of the non-concessioned paved network in the
country.
</P>
<P>
It will also help finance the maintenance of 19,505-km-long
sub-network during the five-year implementation period.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is estimated at 929 million
dollars. The remainder will be financed by the Argentine
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
