<HEADLINE> Northeast China Suffers From Lingering Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province is suffering through the worst drought on record since
the founding of New China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning's precipitation level for the November-February period
fell by some 40 percent on the annual average, with water levels
in the province's seven major reservoirs falling by 43 percent,
according to the Provincial Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
Water has ceased flowing in 18 of 21 major rivers in Fuxin
County.
</P>
<P>
Higher than normal temperatures led to a substantial decline in
soil moisture levels, and complicated the drought conditions
affecting 1.83 million ha. even further, according to Li Wenke,
deputy director of the department.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that Liaoning is combatting severe drought
conditions by proliferating efficient irrigation technology and
strengthening water conservancy efforts.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels have spent 285.6 million yuan
completing 28,000 water-conservancy projects, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
