<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Arrangement for Cote d'Ivoire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) on Tuesday approved a three-year arrangement of 384
million U.S. dollars for Cote d'Ivoire under the Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF).
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to support Cote d'Ivoire's economic
program for 1998-2000.
</P>
<P>
The first annual arrangement of 167 million dollars will be
available in two semi-annual installments. The first installment
of 112 million dollars will be available on March 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
The medium-term adjustment strategy for 1998-2000 focuses on
three key policy components: prudent fiscal policy to bring the
budget close to balance by the year 2000 and achieve a surplus
thereafter, structural reforms to promote private sector
development and investment, and an ambitious social development
agenda focused on poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
The basic macroeconomic objectives for the program are to
achieve a real GDP growth of six percent a year, helping the per
capita income to rise by more than two percent annually; to
maintain an inflation rate of about three percent a year; and to
lower the current account deficit to two percent of GDP by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The ESAF is a concessional IMF facility for assisting member
countries that are undertaking economic reform program to
strengthen their balance of payments and improve their growth
prospects.
</P>
<P>
Cote d'Ivoire joined the IMF in March, 1963. Its quota is
equivalent to 320 million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF
financing currently totals about 448 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
