<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployed Chinese Farmers Now Running Their Own Businesses (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A major economic change is
believed to have take place in rural China as large numbers of
surplus rural laborers who have flooded Chinese cities and coastal
areas in search of work since the mid-1980s return to their
villages and start their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qifa, who spent three years looking for work in north
China, is now the head of three woollen mills with some 200
employees. The 46-year-old man, who was in the army in the late
1970s, went to Beijing along with some other young villagers in
1983 and worked as a salesman for a Beijing woollen mill.
</P>
<P>
He travelled to almost every part of the country before
returning home and starting his own mill in 1985 with money he had
saved.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who now has a great deal of marketing experience and has
gradually come to understand the meaning of things like cost,
profit and market competition, says, "At first, I just wanted to
go out and earn some money, then come back to build a house and
spend the rest of my life, but later I changeed my mind."
</P>
<P>
Last spring, instead of going to town to look for a job as
usual, Wang went to local government departments and got some
information on land and employment policies, and then bought
bricks, tiles and other building materials to start a business of
his own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
