<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crime Rate Declines in South China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Guangdong
Province, a vanguard of China's opening-up drive, not only are
benefiting from economic prosperity but also lower crime rates,
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to a recent provincial political and legal
conference revealed that in 1997 the crime rate in Guangdong
declined 11.3 percent compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that among the province's 21 prefecture-level
cities, the crime rate declined in 16. Of those 16, six dropped
more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of criminal cases of firearms, kidnaping and
robbery fell 52.4 percent, 52.5 percent and 13.9 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
During the past two years, the Pearl River Delta, the most
prosperous region of Guangdong, registered an 11-percent decline
in criminal cases, compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here attribute the improved social order primarily to
the national anti-crime campaign and the establishment of safe
communities across the province.
</P>
<P>
Some 50,000 safe communities now cover 60 percent of the
province's territory.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 63 counties have started police emergency
call service and all of the province's counties now have their own
police patrols.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
