<HEADLINE> Customs Office Helps Develop Export-Oriented Economy in Guizhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIZHOU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Local Customs officials in
southwest China's Guizhou province have played a big role in
promoting the development of an export-oriented economy in this
land-locked province.
</P>
<P>
Since it opened in 1998, the Guiyang Customs Office has helped
the province develop economic ties with other parts of the world,
said Director-General Lian Wensheng.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of export and import companies
registered in the Customs office has increased from a few to
86 over the recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Customs also make efforts to simplify their clearance
procedure to make import and export more efficient, said Lian.
</P>
<P>
The efforts have paid off. According to latest statistics,
Guizhou in 1997 handled 630 million U.S. dollars in imports and
exports, increasing by seven percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the Customs, local products sell well abroad
including metals, electronic and mechanical products, chemicals
and textiles.
</P>
<P>
The province is now making preparations for the opening of
direct container transport by train to Hong Kong,
according to Lian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
