<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Attempts to Ensure Uninterrupted Flow of Yellow River (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- "Rain from the Heavens fill the
Yellow River which then surges forward and empties into a sea of
no return", a well-known poetic line by ancient Tang Dynasty
(618-907) Li Bai seemingly reassures people of the rivers
inexhaustible water resources.
</P>
<P>
However, the poet would most likely never have penned the line
had he known that the water in the middle and lower reaches of the
Yellow River, the cradle of Chinese nation, would stop flowing for
272 days since 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River meanders through China for 5,464 km and is
dubbed as the "mother river of the Chinese nation". The river
finds its sources in the Bayanhar Mountains in northwest China's
Qinghai Province, flows in an easterly direction through nine
provinces and autonomous regions, and empties into the sea in east
China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
 Contributing Problems
</P>
<P>
The river has gone dry more frequently and for longer periods
since the first incidence of interrupted water flow was reported
in the lower reaches in 1972.
</P>
<P>
The root of the problem is largely blamed on inadequate water
resources and sharp increases of water consumption, as well as the
serious waste of water in terms of both production and daily
life, the lack of a unified management system governing the use of
water resources in the Yellow River Valley, and water pollution.
</P>
<P>
Interruptions in the water flow of the Yellow River has caused
great economic damages to the country. Information from east China's
Shandong Province said that its areas in the lower reaches of the
river suffered over 13 billion yuan in economic losses and 3.6
million local population had difficulty of obtaining drinking
water in 1997 alone.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Guangdou, a well-known Chinese hydrologist, said the
problem symbolizes the overall deterioration of the ecological
environment in the entire Yellow River Valley, an area with a
population of well over 140 million people.
</P>
<P>
He noted that continuing environmental deterioration has not
only caused desertification and a loss of biological diversity in
the lower reaches of the river, but has also directly threatened
economic development and the livelihoods of residents in affected
areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Attempts to Ensure Uninterrupted Flow of Yellow River (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Xinhua Writer Hu Lujie and Ding Yaqing
</P>
<P>
Diversion Program
</P>
<P>
Chinese hydrologists have proposed implementation of a
south-north water diversion program to divert water from Yangtze
River in the south to the Yellow River in order to completely
solve problems related to the uninterrupted water flow and
inadequate water resources of the latter river valley.
</P>
<P>
Three options have been formulated for the program -- eastern,
central, western routes. Hydrologists are currently leaning to the
eastern route as the most desirable alternative.
</P>
<P>
The eastern route will involve diverting water from the Yangtze
near Yangzhou City in Jiangsu Province to the Yellow River and
eventually on to Beijing, Tianjin and Hebei Province via the
existing Hangzhou-Beijing Grand Canal and various other rivers
running parallel with the canal.
</P>
<P>
Shandong Province. located in the lower reaches of the Yellow
River, is already diverting water from Yangtze River near Jiangdu
in Jiangsu Province to Dongping Lake, with the current annual
diversion volume estimated at between 800-940 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Realization of the three water diversion routes will require a
combined static investment of 219 billion yuan, with the completed
projects pumping additional 49.3 billion cu.m. of water into the
Yellow River annually.
</P>
<P>
Wu Zhiyao, a well-known Chinese specialist on harnessing of the
Yellow River, called for an immediate execution of the eastern
route as the option is more realistic according to the current
conditions.
</P>
<P>
There would be many practical problems in executing the
south-north water diversion program due to the huge investment
needed and a wide range of technical difficulties in designing and
construction, though the realization of such program will
undoubtedly increase water resources in the Yellow River, said the
specialist who also urged economizing on water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drexler Reported to Coach University of Houston </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Houston Rockets all-star guard
Clyde Drexler will leave the National Basketball Association to
coach his University of Houston, local reports said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Local radio said Drexler might be named to the post as early as
Wednesday and would hire two assistants who were former teammates
on the college club that finished second in the 1983 US college
finals.
