<HEADLINE> Retired Officials Employed as Supervisors in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The municipal government of
Changsha, capital of central China's Hunan Province, has employed
10 retired officials to supervise the working styles of in-service
government officials.
</P>
<P>
Wu Mengnan, a leading official with the municipal disciplinary
inspection commission, remarked at a news conference that the move
is part of the municipal government's effort to build a clean and
honest government.
</P>
<P>
As retired officials, the 10 supervisors are quite familiar
with governmental work and have easy access to the opinions of
ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that by setting up "transfer stations,"
the government could get more candid opinions.
</P>
<P>
Chen Rongjie, 81, has voluntarily acted as a supervisor during
the past dozen years, and has been named by local residents as the
"Pacific Police," namely someone who is concerned about everything.
</P>
<P>
Chen was excited at the news that he is among the 10
supervisors selected, saying: "I'll be an excellent supervisor as
I am no longer a 'self-employed' one." 
</P>
