<HEADLINE> IFC Launches Dollar-Denominated Russian Rouble Bond Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) Tuesday announced the launching of a 100 million
U.S. dollar-denominated Russian rouble-linked global bond issue.
</P>
<P>
The one-year notes carry an annual coupon of 20 percent and
were issued at a price of 97.25 percent of par. The return to
investors is linked to the Russian rouble foreign exchange rate at
the maturity of the notes.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds of the issue will be swapped into U.S. dollar
floating rate funds.
</P>
<P>
The lending manager of the issue is Merrill Lynch
International, London, with seven co-managers in the syndicate
group.
</P>
<P>
The issue, launched on March 12, is expected to be placed with
investors in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
This is IFC's debut launching into the Russian rouble market.
</P>
<P>
The latest transaction, under IFC's Global Medium Term Note
Program, brings IFC's market borrowing to about 3,528 million
dollars since the start of this fiscal year on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and the largest
multilateral source for financing private sector projects in
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
