<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Strengthens Marine Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Zhejiang Province in east China
has imposed more severe compensation fees on persons or units who
discharge pollutants into the sea, with nearly 12 million yuan
(1.5 million U.S. dollars) in fines collected in the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
Work has been done to strengthen water pollution treatment,
which is mainly caused by fishing. The collected compensation fees
will be spent on fostering resources, environmental protection and
administration for fishing, according to the provincial fishing
administration bureau.
</P>
<P>
Twelve monitoring stations for fishing environment have been
set up across the province, and a 60-staff force of fishing
administration has also been established.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang's fishing output is one of the country's biggest,
reaching 2.6 million tons in 1996 to rank first in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
