<HEADLINE> Indian Navy to Update Warships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Defense Ministry of India
has allocated 25 billion rupees (650 million U.S. dollars) for
indigenous production of warships to bolster its aging navy fleet,
a leading Indian daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The project covers construction of three frigates which will be
smaller in tonnage than the Delhi class destroyers (6,500 tons),
said the Indian Express.
</P>
<P>
It would take nearly a year to start construction of these
frigates, named Project 17.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Navy has for the first time used information
technology intensively as a tool in the design of the Project 17
class frigates, which has quickened the entire process.
</P>
<P>
The time-frame for Project 17 from the conception to sanction
stage took the navy four years. The navy refined the design of the
Type 15, or Delhi class destroyer, to develop the Type 17 class
frigate.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India reported Monday that India's cabinet
Committee on Security had approved a plan to build an aircraft
carrier at the cost of 15 billion rupees (390 million U.S.
dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
