<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Government Unveils 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian Government on
Tuesday adopted a draft budget for fiscal 1998 that promises to
rein in the country's runaway hyper-inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian news agency said that under the budget, the
government will keep inflation rate under 45 percent, budget
deficit under 3.6 percent of the nation's Gross Domestic Product
(GDP), and try to achieve a zero economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Under the budget, the government's financial income in 1998
will be 13.3 billion U.S. dollars while spending will reach 14.9
billion dollars, running a deficit of 1.54 billion dollars. The
country's GDP is expected to total 42.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Finance Minister Daniel Dainanu called fiscal 1998 a
harsh year. Experts said the targeted inflation rate, which is far
below the 1997 figure of more than 150 percent, is hard to achieve.
</P>
<P>
The budget was to be submitted to the parliament for review
later this week or early next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
