<HEADLINE> Bomb Blast Targets Hungarian Opposition Party Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A powerful blast caused
extensive damage but no injuries at the home of a Hungarian
opposition party leader, police chief Attila Berta said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At least two kilograms of explosives were detonated in the
overnight blast at the apartment building of Jozsef Torgyan,
chairman of the Small Holder's Party (FKGP), Berta said.
</P>
<P>
The explosion broke all the doors of the six-flat residential
building, tore garage doors out and damaged at least six cars in
the vicinity.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Gabor Kuncze said the blast was an act of
"political terrorism" ahead of the legislative elections scheduled
for May 10.
</P>
<P>
Other political leaders also condemned the attack as "shocking
and irrational."
</P>
<P>
On Friday, police defused a home-made explosive device outside
the Budapest national headquarters of the FKGP, and stepped up
surveillance around party buildings.
</P>
<P>
The incident is now under investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
