<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ranariddh Sentenced to 30 Years for Conspiracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Phnom Penh, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Prince Norodom Ranariddh was
sentenced in his absence to 30 years in prison Wednesday for
conspiring to overthrow the coalition government with the help of
Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
It is the second trial of the deposed first prime minister in
his absence. On March 4, he was convicted of illegally buying and
transporting weapons and sentenced to five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
As in the first trial, Ranariddh, who is self-exile in Bangkok,
chose not put up a defense and refused to recognize the charges
against him.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Funcinpec Party generals Nhiek Bun Chhay,
Serey Kosal and Chao Sambath were all sentenced to 20 years in
prison. General Chao sambath is believed to have been executed in
the wake of the July fighting.
</P>
<P>
The prince and his three co-defendants were charged with
violating three separate laws, one of them the 1994 statute
outlawing the Khmer Rouge, which carries a maximum life sentence
and a minimum of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The other two laws relate to the criminal and military
violation of national security.
</P>
<P>
An agreement signed by the prince and nominal Khmer Rouge
leader Khieu Samphan was a key part of the prosecution, along with
other evidence alleging an aggressive military alliance between
the prince and the rebel faction.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two witnesses, including the prince's former military
adviser, Tum Sambol, now military adviser to First Prime Minister
Ung Huot, testified at the Military Court trial.
</P>
<P>
The witnesses were mainly former Funcinpec Party military and
police commanders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
