<HEADLINE> Mostar Airport to be Opened for Civilian Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The international mediator in
Bosnia has imposed a decision that the airport in the divided city
of Mostar will reopen to civilian traffic within a month.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Westendorp, who is responsible for implementing the
Dayton peace accord, decided Tuesday to open the airfield which
has been closed to all but NATO flights since the beginning of the
war in 1992.
</P>
<P>
His spokesman, Simon Haselock, announced in Sarajevo that the
mayor and deputy mayor of Mostar would each nominate three people
for a seven-member committee, which is in charge of the airport.
</P>
<P>
The seventh, the chairman of the committee, would be nominated
by Westendorp, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
This arrangement will be valid for six months while Bosnian
Croat and Muslim leaders seek a long-term solution to the
management of the airport.
</P>
<P>
Haselock said that Westendorp exercised his power to impose
legally binding decisions to meet the economic needs of Mostar, an
important strategic post 100 kilometers south of Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
Croatians and Moslims there had not reached an agreement
to run the airport after months of discussion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
