<HEADLINE> Kyrgyzstan Government to Commit to Social Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Top priority will be given to
reforms in the social sectors this year, Kyrgyzstani President
Askar Akayev said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a State Union Report to the parliament, Akayev said, greater
efforts will be made this year to address some of the social
problems, including inadequate management, the rules and laws yet
to be perfected and inefficiencies in the health-care system.
</P>
<P>
Akayev said his administration would appropriate 59 percent of
its gross domestic product (GDP) to social welfare, the highest
among the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS).
</P>
<P>
Also a new budget plan will be drawn to guarantee financial
support for social development programs, he added.
</P>
<P>
On his nation's current political and economic situations,
Akayev said Kyrgyzstan had seen the realization of a stable
macro-economy, and amity and unity among different nationalities
which have set the stage for future economic development. 
</P>
