<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Asian Nations Agree on Sharing Water Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The prime ministers of Kazakhstan,
Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan reached a five-year agreement on Tuesday on
the sharing of water resources.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed following talks in the Kyrgyzstan capital
of Bishkek, determined compensation to be paid by Kazakhstan and
Uzbekistan for their use of the water resources of Kyrgystan.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time the three Central Asian countries, which
have a combined population of 40 million, have established a
formal arrangement on the issue.
</P>
<P>
With the largest amount of fresh water among the five-country
central Asian economic union, Kyrgyzstan had been providing free
water to neighboring countries for irrigation of farm land.
</P>
<P>
Last spring, however, Kyrgyzstan started to cut the supplies
and talks leading to the compensation agreement began. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
