<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Elected-President Promises to Control Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica's President-elect
Miguel Angel Rodriguez said Tuesday that his government would
control spending and guarantee economic stability.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez, who will take office on May 8, told businessmen that
the number of cabinet members will be reduced from 22 to 11 and
the funding to domestic sports games would be cut by half to
around 2.8 million U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez, a lawyer and candidate of the Social Christian Unity
Party, obtained 47 percent of the total votes, defeating Social
Democrat candidate Jose Miguel Corrales in the February 1 election.
</P>
<P>
He had proposed national corporatization, but this would be
difficult to achieve because of the proposals for privatization
and the elimination of state monopolies in some key economic
sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
