<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auto Imports Decline, Exports up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Despite tariff cuts on vehicle
imports last October, automobile and motorcycle imports declined
sharply, and their exports increased dramatically last year,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The import volume of automobiles and motor vehicles was 1.81
billion U.S. dollars, down 12.08 percent from 1996, and the export
volume reached 825 million U.S.dollars, up 21.12 percent,
according to the General Administration of Customs.
</P>
<P>
Motorcycle imports reached 1,495 units, down 48.6 percent, and
the volume hit 2.37 million U.S. dollars, up 56.72 percent.
</P>
<P>
Car imports stood at 33,300 units, down 40 percent, with the
total value reaching 300 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports of luxury sedans saw a dramatic increase last year, but
import of medium-sized cars fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
Japan was the largest auto exporter to China last year, earning
370 million U.S. dollars on 21,700 units sold.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that increasingly sophisticated mind-sets of
would-be car-buyer, an overcapacity in the domestic market and
steep drops in auto prices would lead to a continuing slide of
auto imports this year.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, China exported 14,800 vehicles last year, earning
190 million U.S. dollars, up 28.83 percent from 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
