<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Insists on Demarcating Sea Borders With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine insists on demarcating the
Ukraine-Russia borders in the Black Sea, the Azov Sea and the
Kerich Strait in line with international laws, a Ukrainian
official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Anto Buterko, first Deputy Foreign Minister of Ukraine, said
his country believed it was necessary to determine related
countries' boundaries in these areas according to international
laws.
</P>
<P>
The legal status of the Sea of Azov should be determined, he
said, adding that the Sea should be the inner water of Ukraine and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Buterko also asked for the continental shelves of the Azov Sea
and the Black Sea to be determined.
</P>
<P>
The demarcation should be completed by 1999 under a
Ukraine-Russia accord, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Azov Sea and the Black Sea are encircled by the territories
of Ukraine and Russia.
</P>
<P>
During Ukraine President Leonid Kuchma's Russia tour in
February, the two countries agreed to begin the demarcation in the
first quarter of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
