<HEADLINE> Exchanges Increase Between Guangdong Province, Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 18 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province has been striving to expand exchanges and cooperation
with Taiwan by making good use of its advantages.
</P>
<P>
Different ports of exit and entry in the province reportedly
received 2 million compatriots from Taiwan in 1997, a rise of
220,000 people over 1996, said local sources.
</P>
<P>
Coastal areas of the province also received more than 1,500
fishing boats with 5,000 fishermen from Taiwan in the past year,
according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, exchanges increased in such fields as
economics, culture, science and technology, and sports. A total of
679 people from Guangdong went to Taiwan on exchange programs
which brought back more than 260 people from different walks of
life in Taiwan to Guangdong in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Different localities of Guangdong Province have been taking
pains to improve their investment environment and enhancing
service awareness toward Taiwan-backed businesses.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong is now home to more than 8,824 Taiwan-financed
enterprises, of which, 524 were started in 1997 with contractual
investment exceeding 610 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The province shipped 1.43 billion U.S. dollars worth of
commodities to Taiwan and purchased 10.46 billion U.S. dollars
worth of commodities from the island province in the past year,
said local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
