<HEADLINE> Tibet Plans to Promote Opening-up Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region in
southwest China plans to strengthen international cooperation and
exchanges this year to promote the formation of an overall
opening-up pattern.
</P>
<P>
Gyalcan Norbu, chairman of the Tibet Autonomous Regional
Government, said that the opening-up drive has resulted in marked
progress in all aspects of Tibet life and has produced a driving
force in the development of the regional economy.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Tibet should also intensify its cooperation
with the rest of the country, particularly with coastal provinces,
and foster key sectors for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The chairman stressed that the autonomous region should set up
the notion of sharing interests with partners instead of pursuing
free assistance.
</P>
<P>
With a border of 3,800 kilometers, Tibet has 20 traditional
trading ports and constitutes an economic beachhead into South
Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said that, in 1998, the autonomous region plans to give
priority to improving the region's economic competitive edge and
establishing export-oriented production bases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
