<HEADLINE> Senior Officer on Governing Troops in HK with Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Practices have shown that the
People's Liberation Army (PLA) troops stationed in the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) have implemented very well the
policy of "one country, two systems" over the past eight months
since Hong Kong's return, a senior officer said.
</P>
<P>
The troops have conducted effective defense and other duties,
setting up essential contacts with the Hong Kong SAR government,
and adapted themselves to the natural and social circumstances of
Hong Kong, said Xiong Ziren, political commissar of the troops.
</P>
<P>
"The main reason behind is that we have resolutely implemented
the policy of governing the army according to law, so that our
troops have won good reputation from Hong Kong residents," Xiong
said at a panel discussion of deputies to the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC) from the PLA.
</P>
<P>
Under the new situation, he noted, governing the army in
accordance with law is the guarantee for carrying out the duties
of the troops.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Xiong suggested, certain laws or regulations
should be enacted for the appraisal of the merits of officers and
make good arrangements to displace them when they are transferred
to civilian work from the army stationed in Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
