<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Cut Allowances for Government Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has approved a
Finance Ministry proposal to cut housing allowances and travel and
mobile-telephone expenses for all government officials.
</P>
<P>
Deputy government spokesman Pan Phuengsujarit said Tuesday that
government officials will also be banned from receiving housing
allowances and travel expenses to an area in which they request to
be relocated.
</P>
<P>
Today's Nation newspaper quoted Pan as saying that the
government will not allow officials to get reimbursement for
housing allowance if their agencies are relocated.
</P>
<P>
Pan said the government was informed that when the Public
Health Ministry moved from the Want Thewet district to the
Nonthaburii district in Bangkok, the state's housing expenses rose
from 80 million baht (2 million U.S. dollars) to 200 million baht
(5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Expenses for moving house and for mobile phones will no longer
be paid in full but be subject to a limit. A mobile-phone owner
exceeding the limit must pay the balance, said Pan.
</P>
<P>
He said that in addition to this, government officials
stationed overseas will face a 20-percent cut in special
allowances.
</P>
<P>
Under the Finance Ministry proposal, the Royal Degree on
Housing Allowances 1984 and the Royal Degree on Travel Expenses
1983 will be amended so that all officials will be barred from
being reimbursed for housing allowances in areas where their own
house or that of a spouse, parent or child is located. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
