<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers on China's Peaceful Reunification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China's peaceful reunification
has become one of the most popular topics among deputies to the
Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), China's top lawmaking
body, in session here since early March.
</P>
<P>
Many lawmakers said that the successful practice of the
principle of "one country, two systems" in Hong Kong has greatly
boosted their confidence in the ultimate reunification of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Zhang Yongjun, a native of Taipei in Taiwan, said that
the principle of "one country, two systems" has is based on the
fundamental interests of the Chinese nation and has taken both
historical factors and realities into account.
</P>
<P>
"The smooth return of Hong Kong to its motherland and its
continued prosperity and stability could serve as a successful
model for the return of Macao and the settlement of the Taiwan
issue," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Edmund Hau Wah Ho from Macao, which will return to China
at the end of next year, said Macao people are fully confident in
the region's future.
</P>
<P>
"It has become a common understanding among the Macao people
that Hong Kong today is Macao tomorrow," said Ho, who is
vice-chairman of the Macao Chinese General Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Wilfred Wong Ying-wai from the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) said that Hong Kong's return to the
motherland on July 1 last year has provided new opportunities for
Hong Kong's further development, and enabled China's interior to
take full advantage of Hong Kong's status as a global financial,
trade and shipping center.
</P>
<P>
"Once Macao returns to the motherland and the Taiwan issue is
also resolved, the Chinese nation will acquire an unprecedented
opportunity to seek great prosperity," he predicted.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Liang Guangda, who is Party secretary of Zhuhai, a
booming city next to Macao in south China's Guangdong Province,
said his city is now making active efforts to prepare for the
return of Macao.
</P>
<P>
"An exit-and-entry control mansion with 90 passages, the
largest in the country, has been built, while construction of a
bridge linking Zhuhai and Macao is underway," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Liu Yiming pointed to the fact that since the political
problems between the two sides of the Taiwan Straits remain
unresolved, the expansion of cross-Straits exchanges has been
affected negatively by some imposed obstacles from the Taiwan side.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, Taiwan itself has been prevented from seeking
greater development through exploiting the affluent resources and
huge market on the Chinese mainland," he said with regret. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
