<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Set to Merge Supermarket Chains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
commercial center, plans to improve efficiency by introducing
mergers to reduce its number of supermarket chains from 14 to
10.
</P>
<P>
The city's first supermarket chain was established in 1992,
with the sector thereafter witnessing booming growth and the total
number peaking at 40 chains.
</P>
<P>
However, low-level operational scales resulted in low
efficiency and triggered a round of mergers. The total of 28
supermarkets chains in place at the end of last year has since
dwindled to only 14 operational units.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the 14 operational supermarket chains in
place at the end of 1997 had 919 outlets stores covering 330,000
square meters. Related outlets recorded total sales of some 10
billion yuan (1.20 billion US dollars), making up 6.7 percent
of the city's total retail sales.
</P>
<P>
The municipal plan calls for future supermarkets to have floor
space of some 1000 square meters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
