<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Firms Shine in Civilian Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- China's vast number of military
firms are playing an increasingly prominent role in civilian
production as makers of passenger aircraft, motor vehicles,
electrical appliances, toothpaste and toothbrushes.
</P>
<P>
In Xi'an, capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province, dozens
of civilian manufacturing bases led by former military firms have
emerged, according to Feng Xichu, mayor of Xi'an and a deputy to
the National People's Congress (NPC), in session here since early
March.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an is home to 68 military enterprises and research
institutes with a workforce of more than 200,000. In 1997, the
city's defence industry produced an output value of close to 10
billion yuan, of which 75 percent came from civilian products,
Feng said.
</P>
<P>
When it comes to military enterprises making more civilian
products than military equipment, Xi'an is not alone. In southwest
China, another major military production base, civilian production
makes up more than 95 percent of the total production of the
defence industry there.
</P>
<P>
A shining example is Sichuan's Mianyang City, the country's
second biggest electronics industry center. Changhong Electronics
Group in the city, which has its origin in a defence enterprise,
produced 17 billion yuan worth of civilian goods in 1996, 54
percent of the industrial and agricultural output value of the
city of the year with a population of five million.
</P>
<P>
By now, military firms in China have built up more than 600
civilian production lines, turning out 15,000 kinds of civilian
products, their lines of business ranging from telecoms, energy,
transport, light and textile industry to pharmaceutical and
medical products and engineering construction.
</P>
<P>
Civilian production in China's defence industry has grown by 20
percent annually in recent years, and the proportion of civilian
production today accounts for 80 percent of the industry's total
production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Restricts Anti-Nerve Gas Drug Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Defense Department
said Tuesday it will withhold the anti-nerve gas drug implicated
in the Gulf War syndrome unless a specific gas attack is imminent.
</P>
<P>
The drug, pyridostygmine bromide, or PB, was a valuable and
necessary element of defense against chemical weapons attacks,
said Gary Christopherson, acting assistant secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
But in the future, he said in a letter to the Senate Veterans'
Affairs Committee, it will be used only if intelligence indicates
imminent use of nerve agents Soman or Tabun against U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
During the 1991 Gulf War, the U.S. military gave PB to about
600,000 troops without their consent although the Pentagon had no
reason to believe Soman and Tabun were being used.
</P>
<P>
Instead, said an Associate Press report, intelligence indicated
Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein had stockpiles of the nerve gas Sarin.
</P>
<P>
Later, thousands of veterans have complained of undiagnosed
illnesses such as chronic fatigue, headaches, nausea, diarrhea,
depression, joint and muscle pain, memory loss and insomnia.
</P>
<P>
One theory says such illnesses may have been the result of
troop exposure to chemical weapons. Another theory suggests the
combination of PB and an insecticide called Deet as the cause.
</P>
<P>
Senator Jay Rockefeller of West Virginia, ranking Democrat on
the Senate committee, said the limited use for the drug suggests
the Pentagon never should have given it to Gulf War troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Herdsmen in China to End Nomadic Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- All herdsmen are expected to end
the nomadic life by the end of the century, according to Qi
Jingfa, vice-minister of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The government began assisting roaming herdsmen to settle down
12 years ago. With adequate and persevering endeavors made over
the past years, 97 percent herdsmen in the northern Inner Mongolian
Autonomous Region and 75.6 percent of herdsmen in northwestern
Gansu Province settled down by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 67 percent and 54 percent of herdsmen in Qinghai
Province and the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, also in
northwest China, had dwelled in the new houses they had built by
the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Practices have shown that settlement of local herdsmen helps
develop animal husbandry in a large scale and promote cultural,
technological and educational undertakings in the pastoral areas,"
Qi Jingfa said.
</P>
<P>
The way of settling down is also the best option for herdsmen
in need to become better off or become affluent, he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Internal Matter, Milosevic Repeats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Kosovo is an internal affair of
Yugoslavia, President Slobodan Milosevic claimed again Tuesday,
when he met with visiting Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported that Milosevic said
the Kosovo issue could only be solved by political means within
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Exerting pressure or intervention on internal affairs did not
accord with international policy which initiates the establishment
of equality and mutual trust between countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Plimakov said Kosovo should be given a new position beyond
cultural autonomy, under safeguarded Yugoslav territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister, who arrived in Belgrade on a two-day
visit to Yugoslavia, called on Kosovo Albanian extremists to stop
terror activities and Yugoslav authorities to give up using
large-scale military force against Kosovo Albanians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
