<BODY>
<HEADLINE> University Team to Scale 8,201m Mt. Cho Oyu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- A mountaineering team from the
Beijing University will scale the 8,201-meter Mt. Cho Oyu next
month to celebrate the centennial anniversary of the founding of
the university.
</P>
<P>
The 17-member team, including one professor, three
master-degree candidates and five graduates, will attempt to be
the first university team in China to conquer a peak over 8,000
meters.
</P>
<P>
The mountain, sixth highest in the world, is located on the
Sino-Nepalese border. It was conquered for the first time by an
Austrian and two Nepalese sherpas from an Austrian team in October
1954.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing University squad will leave here on Friday and is
expected to arrive at the base camp in China's Tibetan Autonomous
Region on March 28 before setting off their assault on the summit
on May 1.
</P>
<P>
The university team has successfully scaled six mountains in
nine years, including the 7,546-meter Mt. Muztagata.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing University was founded on May 4, 1898. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
