<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Deputies Confident of Success in Fight against Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Deputies to the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC), in session here since early March, said
corruption can be effectively held in check with in-depth reform
and the establishment of a legal system suited for a socialist
market economy.
</P>
<P>
A sample survey among 157 NPC deputies shows that more than 70
percent of the deputies believe corruption will be held in check
in a short period of time, and 99 percent of deputies express
confidence in the success of the ongoing anti-corruption campaign.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Qitong, an NPC deputy and chairman of the Standing
Committee of Fujian Provincial People's Congress, said that the
gradual improvement of a legal framework in line with a socialist
market economy has laid the foundation for fighting corruption.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978, China's top legislature has enacted 328 laws and
law-related decisions and its government has formulated more than
700 regulations. In addition, provinces, autonomous regions and
centrally-administered municipalities have formulated more than
5,000 local laws and regulations. Such laws and regulations have
formed a legal framework guiding economic activities and people's
behaviors, Yuan said.
</P>
<P>
Also, a series of laws regulating the activities of
law-enforcement officials such as the police, judges and
prosecutors have been enacted. And people's congresses at all
levels have intensified supervision over the implementation of
laws and regulations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yuan said that Chinese leaders have on many occasions stressed
the importance of fighting corruption, noting that this conforms
with the wish of the Chinese people to eradicate corruption.
</P>
<P>
While foreseeing a bright prospect in the fight against
corruption, many NPC deputies acknowledge that anti-corruption
will be a long-term and arduous task.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
