<HEADLINE> Thailand to Launch Global Crime Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and the United States
are planning to launch an international academy here late this
year in a bid to provide training in the suppression of narcotics
and other transnational crimes, the Bangkok Post reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Winer, the U.S. deputy assistant secretary of state,
said Tuesday that the academy will help prepare officials in the
Asian region to deal with major organized crime.
</P>
<P>
The academy will allow countries of the region to combat drugs,
money laundering, financial crime, illegal immigrants and
violation of international property rights, Winer said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. help to set up an international law enforcement
academy in Thailand was part of the package of assistance pledged
during Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai's recent talks with U.S.
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
As Thailand expects to pass its Money Laundering Bill soon,
Winer said the United States wants to see the region adopt similar
standards because it will promote financial stability and increase
market confidence.
</P>
<P>
The question of Myanmar's participation was "still being
discussed", said Winer. 
</P>
