<HEADLINE> U.S. Against Kosovo's Bid for Independence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Washington is against Kosovo's bid
for independence from Yugoslavia, U.S. Assistant Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott said Tuesday in Skoplje.
</P>
<P>
As quoted by reports from the Macedonian capital, where Talbott
was on a one-day tour, he warned that, if escalated, the ethnic
conflict in Kosovo could be worse than that in Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Describing the recent tension in Kosovo as "explosive" and the
"most dangerous" in Europe, the U.S. official said his government
has been following the developments in the breakaway province.
</P>
<P>
Once spilled out from Kosovo in southern Serbia, where 90
percent of residents are ethnic Albanians, the crisis could
trigger a war involving a number of other countries, Talbott said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States and the international community do not
support Kosovo's independence or breakaway from Yugoslavia," he
said, adding there should be no reason to change the borders.
</P>
<P>
He called, together with Macedonian Foreign Minister Blagoj
Handziski, for earlier dialogues between Belgrade and Kosovo
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
To address the risk of the Kosovo crisis spreading into
Macedonia, Talbott suggested the United Nations peacekeeping
forces in Macedonia should stay or be replaced by other troops.
</P>
<P>
The current mandate of the U.N. troops will expire August 31.
</P>
<P>
"There should be no defense vacuum in Macedonia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Talbott, who arrived at Skoplje on Monday evening after visits
to Croatia and Albania, was scheduled to continue his Balkan tour
into Bulgaria and Romania on Tuesday evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
