<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Set Up 500 Youth Training Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will set up 500
vocational training centers for youth by year 2000 to resolve the
unemployment problem here which is expected to be aggravated with
the culmination of the 15-year civil war, the official Daily News
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vocational Training and Rural Industries Minister Amarasiri
Dodangoda was quoted as saying that already 171 provincial
training centers and 11 district centers have been set up
countrywide to train youth in typewriting, shorthand, scientific
dress making, beauty culture and motor cycle repairing.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the government's efforts to resolve the
unemployment problem, the private sector and non-governmental
organizations have been mobilized.
</P>
<P>
The main problem was to find employment for those who pass out
from schools and universities to suit their academic
qualifications.
</P>
<P>
There were thousands of unemployed people who were certificate
holders and therefore it was necessary to provide some sort of
vocational training to enable them to be self employed or qualify
for jobs in the private sector or abroad, the minister said at a
rally recently, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
There was demand from abroad for technicians such as welders,
pipe fitters, jewelers and wood technologists. These offers should
be taken up for the benefit of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Vocational Training Authority, however, plans to train at
least 15,000 young people this year and increase its capacity to
25,000 by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
