<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Opens Financial Sector Wider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- This largest economic center of
China continued to open its financial sector last year, according
to a senior banker.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's number of operational overseas financial
institutions rose by four to 51 by the end of last year, said Mao
Yingliang, president of the Shanghai branch of the People's Bank
of China, the central bank.
</P>
<P>
He added that the licensed overseas financial institutions
represent 15 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Also last year overseas financial institutions opened 18 new
representative offices in Shanghai, bringing to 163 the
municipality's total number of such offices.
</P>
<P>
The experimentation in yuan business by nine overseas banks in
the Pudong New Area has produced positive effects, Mao said,
adding that more oversas banks will be approved to deal in the
local currency this year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 24 licensed overseas banks have moved their branch
offices to Pudong, a rising finance and trade zone separated from
downtown Shanghai by the Huangpu River.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the 45 overseas financial
institutions in the banking business in Shanghai had 17.6 billion
U.S. dollars in assets by the end of last year, up 29 percent from
a year ago. Their outstanding loans were up 48 percent to 13.3
billion U.S. dollars while their unpaid deposits rose 39 percent
to 1.9 billion U.S. dollars. Their post-tax profit grew 28 percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
The overseas banks saw their overdue loans down slightly to
1.15 percent of their lending portfolio last year, while the
majority of their loans were directed to such industries as
electronics, chemicals, manufacturing, finance, and transportation.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded insurance companies in Shanghai reported a
combined premium income of 616 million yuan last year, up 23.2
percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
The influence of overseas financial institutions in Shanghai
has spread to neighboring areas, with 56 percent of loans extended
to borrowers outside Shanghai, Mao said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
