<HEADLINE> China Calls for Cooperation at Human Rights Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Chinese diplomat
said Tuesday that common ground and cooperation should be sought
during the 54th session of the Commission on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jianmin, the head of the Chinese delegation to the session,
made the remark at a meeting discussing the agenda of the present
session, which began on Monday and will end on April 24.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the 53 member states of the commission came
from five continents with different historical and cultural
background, it was natural for them to have different views on
this or that question.
</P>
<P>
But more importantly, he said, the member states had much
common ground.
</P>
<P>
"For instance, we all recognize the universality of human
rights; we are all committed to the promotion and protection of
human rights; we all agree that no country's human rights
situation is perfect, there is always room for improvement."
</P>
<P>
"It is for us to identify our common ground and create an
atmosphere of equality and mutual respect for cooperation," Wu
said.
</P>
<P>
Only under the spirit of cooperation, on the basis of equality
and mutual respect , can the Human Rights Commission find its way
out of the blind alley of useless confrontation, he said. 
</P>
