<HEADLINE> Isaksson Wins Golden Double in World Cup Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Home favorite Patrick Isaksson
won his golden double by taking both the 50-meter and 200-meter
breaststroke titles on the first day of a two-day World Cup
swimming meeting in Malmo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Isaksson, the 100m breaststroke winner at last April's
short course championships in Gothenburg, savored his big win in
the 200m, which was not his speciality, by beating some of the
world's best including world record holder Phil Rogers of
Australia.
</P>
<P>
He clocked two minutes 10.42 seconds in the 200, ahead of
European champion Alexander Goukov in second on 2:11.04 and
Australia's Ryan Mitchell in 2:11.35. Rogers finished fourth.
</P>
<P>
"What was good was to beat three people who can swim about 2:08
and especially Mitchell who I haven't swum against before,"
Isaksson said.
</P>
<P>
Isaksson, who won a double victory in the last World Cup in
Sheffield, England, at the weekend in the 50 and 100 meters,
considered the 100 his best event.
</P>
<P>
Early, Isaksson won the 50 meters in 27.80 seconds, ahead of
Dominico Fioravanti of Italy on 28.21.
</P>
<P>
Christian Keller of Germany became another double gold medalist
by winning both the 400m and 100m individual races.
</P>
<P>
He took the 400 meters in a time of 4:13.40, more than a second
clear of Canada's Curtis Myden and won the 100 meters in 55.43,
ahead of Denmark's Jakob Andersen on 55.51.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 200 freestyle, Louise Joehncke of Sweden edged
Costa Rica's Claudia Poll, the 1996 Olympic champion, for the top
honor in 1:58.26, 0.09 seconds ahead of Poll. 
</P>
</TEXT>
