<HEADLINE> Philippines Approves Deal With IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
approved a two-year-long precautionary program with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) which is expected to be
implemented in April, the Business Daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Memorandum for Economic and Financial Policies (MEEP) has
already been signed by Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson and
Finance Secretary Salvador Enriquez, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum, which will replace the existing IMF program for
the country, will be forwarded for approval to the IMF executive
board which would meet on March 28 or 29, Enriquez was quoted as
saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, the country's gross national product is
expected to grow by 3 percent in 1998, and 4 to 5 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Average inflation would be kept at between 7.5 and 8.5 percent
this year, and at 6 to 7 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum also provides for banking reforms, which include
an increase in minimum capital, higher provisioning and reducing
intermediation costs.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is expected to exit from the decades-long IMF
economic supervision after it graduates from the present IMF
program at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
But the government entered the so-called precautionary
arrangement program with the IMF in order to obtain billions of
dollars of loans to cope with the current currency crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
