<HEADLINE> China-Canada Project Benefits Uygur Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Supihan, a woman farmer in
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, received a 600-yuan loan from a
China-Canada project six months ago. She has not only paid back
the loan but also has earned an additional 550 yuan.
</P>
<P>
She was one of 320 poor Uygur women in Yiliqi Township of Hotan
city in northwest China who received the aid from the five-year
income-creating project for women, coded the CC97 Program.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Canadian government provided 4.6 million Canadian
dollars of free aid to 320 Uygur women farmers in four villages of
the city to help them improve life.
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent of the women spent the loan fattening cattle and
sheep, while the rest were involved in small businesses and
growing vegetables. All of them have improved their living
conditions by varying margins, and now they have received a second
loan of 1,000 yuan each.
</P>
<P>
The loan recipients also participated in training in health
care, environmental protection, animal husbandry, forestry, and
literacy organized by the program administration office.
</P>
<P>
The Canadians will have another 640 Uygur women join the
program and increase the annual loan in the next four years, local
sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
