<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- The paper banner headlined in red letters the news that Zhu
Rongji was approved to be premier of the State Council, China's
cabinet, by the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) at a full
session yesterday morning.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wannian and Chi Haotian were approved as Vice-Chairmen of
the Central Military Commission. Fu Quanyou, Yu Yongbo, Wang Ke
and Wang Ruilin were appointed members of the Central Military
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yang was elected President of the Supreme People's Court
and Han Zhubin was chosen as Procurator-General of the Supreme
People's Procuratorate.
</P>
<P>
-- The paper carried four colored photos including newly-chosen
Premier Zhu Rongji, President Jiang Zemin shaking hands with Zhu
and Zhu Rongji shaking hands with former Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
-- The country will strengthen the assessment of the
proficiency of managers of the state-owned enterprises and those
unqualified managers will not be allowed to take their posts again
or take new posts in other ventures.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- A feature story tells of Jiang Zemin, General Secretary of
the CPC Central Committee, concerned over the miners by writing a
letter to a NPC deputy in charge of Shanxi Province's mining
work. He urged the miners to pay more attention to safety in work.
</P>
<P>
-- Deputies to the Ninth NPC were almost unanimous in
entrusting Zu Rongji with China's top administrative post. Zhu
recieved a lengthy ovation when elected in the Great Hall of the
People.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, 69, a vice-premier for seven years, was largely
responsible for macroeconomic control. He is best known for
curbing inflation without stifling growth.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Deputies to the Ninth NPC called for greater efforts for
preventing environmental pollution and seeking a sustainable
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
They believed that the country should develop economy based on
knowledge, or science, seeking the best non-polluting resources
that could be found.
</P>
<P>
-- China welcomes US President Bill Clinton's decision to move
up his visit to China, says a Foreign Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and US officials are preparing for the visit, scheduled
for late June, Zhu Bangzao said yesterday in Beijing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
