<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ewing Hopes to Return for Playoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 17 (Xinhua) -- New York Knicks center Patrick
Ewing, who received his wrist surgery in December, said on Tuesday
he hoped to return to the court for the season's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
Ewing, 35, who was expected to be sidelined until next season,
said "my goal is to definitely come back for the playoffs. If it
were up to me, I would play tonight."
</P>
<P>
Ewing, a 2.13 meter star center at his 13th NBA year, suffered
a dislocated right wrist and torn ligaments on December 20.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year-old veteran had the cast and three pins removed on
February 15, triggering speculation he could return if the Knicks
make the playoffs. Playoff rosters must be set by April 20.
</P>
<P>
Ewing, 11-time NBA All-Star, increased his range of motion to
60 percent and his strength to 50 percent 12 weeks after the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
"All through the rehab and all through the time in the cast, I
kept my mind strong. I kept thinking about coming back," added
Ewing, whose team has gone 20-18 in his absence.
</P>
<P>
The Knicks stand sixth in the Eastern Conference in a tight
race for the eight East playoff berths.
</P>
<P>
Ewing, who signed a four-year 68 million dollars contract
during the offseason, was averaging team highs of 20.8 points and
10.2 rebounds before the injury.
</P>
<P>
He eclipsed 22,000 career points earlier this season and needs
222 rebounds to become just the sixth player in history with
20,000 points and 10,000 rebounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
