<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Danish Liberal Party Leader Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The head of Denmark's Liberal
Party has resigned after his center-right opposition coalition
lost the general election on March 11.
</P>
<P>
Uffe Ellemann-Jensen, 56, was due to give a press conference
later Tuesday to explain his decision.
</P>
<P>
Elected to parliament for the first time in 1977,
Ellemann-Jensen was foreign minister from 1982 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll published before voting indicated the
center-right alliance of the Liberals and Conservatives would
defeat the center-left ruling coalition of the Social Democrats
and the Radicals led by Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen, and
Ellemann-Jensen would have become Denmark's next prime minister.
</P>
<P>
However, the ruling coalition won the election, taking 90 seats
in the 179-seat parliament. Ellemann-Jensen's opposition was one
seat behind. Rasumssen will remain in power to form the next
cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
