<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT 0100, March 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain's former cabinet minister Jonathan Aitken was
released Tuesday on bail after being questioned over allegations
of perjury and conspiracy to pervert the course of justice.
</P>
<P>
The 55-year-old official was arrested earlier in the day after
he offered himself for police questioning. His 17-year-old
daughter, Victoria, was arrested Monday over allegations of
conspiracy to pervert the course of justice. (UK-Ex-Minister)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Tuesday
reported delays in Angola's peace process and recommended adding
83 civilian police observers to the United Nations Observer
Mission in Angola.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the Security Council, the U.N. chief said that
delays and last-minutes conditions "have become a constant
feature" of the tactics of the National Union for the Total
Independence fo Angola (UNITA). (UN-Annan-Angola)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian Foreign Ministry announced a decision
Tuesday to expel two Norwegian diplomats from Russia, the Interfax
news service reported.
</P>
<P>
The two Norwegians -- Rune Castberg, a councillor of the
Norwegian embassy in Moscow, and Ole Bjornoy, consul of the
Norwegian general consulate in Murmansk -- were ordered to leave
Russia by March 20. (Russia-Norway-Diplomats)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- The four parties having talks on the Korean Peninsula
have agreed that the talks have now turned from procedural matters
into a phase of discussions on substantial issues.
</P>
<P>
China, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), South
Korea and the United States of America have also agreed to make
concerted efforts for further progress of the talks, Chen Jian,
assistant foreign minister of China, said here Tuesday. (Korean
Peninsula-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- World oil demand is forecast to reach 75.1 million
barrels a day in 1998, representing an increase of 1.6 million b/d
from 1997, when the growth was 1.8 million barrels b/d.
</P>
<P>
Citing the figures of the International Energy Agency, the
U.S. Journal of Commerce said Tuesday that the slowdown trend is
due to the Asian financial crisis. (World Oil Demand)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Banjamin Netanyahu has cut
short his meeting here Tuesday evening with visiting British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook as planned, Netanyahu's office said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu also decided not to host a dinner in
honor of Cook as formerly planned, the office
added. (Israel-England)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt on Tuesday expressed confidence in the upcoming
visit of United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan to the Middle
East, saying it will give a better chance to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt has great confidence in the secretary general and his
mission as well as the role of the United Nations," Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters on the eve of Annan's
tour of the region. (Egypt-Annan-Visit) 
</P>
</TEXT>
