<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Service Sector Contributing Factor in Shanghai's Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The service sector has become a
major contributor to economic growth in Shanghai, accounting for
44 percent of the more than 336 billion yuan of gross domestic
product (GDP) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The service sector registered 153 billion yuan in added value
last year, a 17.7 percent rise from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of the amount, banking and insurance businesses generated 47.25
billion yuan of added value, a 26 percent rise over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Stock Exchange conducted more than 2,980 billion
yuan in turnover last year and the local China Foreign Exchange
Trading Center dealt with 69.71 billion U.S. dollars in turnover.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, all banks in the city had had more than
556 billion yuan of savings and 372 billion yuan for loans. The
city had 2,634 Chinese banking institutions and 11 insurance
companies by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Last year, added value generated by local posts and
telecommunications, transportation, commercial businesses, and
real estate rose 8.4 percent, 4.6 percent, 21.2 percent and 15.3
percent, respectively, over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai plans to place more emphasis on improving the
framework of the service sector and boosting new economy-driving
forces like real estate markets, urban tourism and information
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
