<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roger Milla Ready to Coach Cameroon for World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Cameroon's retired star Roger
Milla said he was ready to take the helm of coaching his national
soccer squad for the World Cup finals in France this summer.
</P>
<P>
Local reports on Tuesday quoted Milla as saying that "Cameroon
still has a coach at the moment. But I've already been contacted,
and I am ready because it would be a very exciting job."
</P>
<P>
In 1990, Milla scored four goals to pace the Indomitable Lions
to the quarterfinals in the World Cup in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Cameroon did not lose a game en route to qualifying for the
World Cup under Belgian coach Henri Depieux who was replaced for
the last game against Zimbabwe by Jean Manga Onguene.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Milla works as an assistant coach in Montpellier,
the southern French city where Cameroon will face Italy in Group B.
</P>
<P>
In a group which also features Chile and Austria, Milla said
that "our players have only started their national team careers.
It's a young team, perhaps some stars will emerge during the World
Cup."
</P>
<P>
Milla, the Africa's player of the year in 1976 and 1990, said
Italy was the favorite to advance and Austria could also make the
second round.
</P>
<P>
In the 1994 World Cup in the United States, Milla, 42, scored
his team's only goal in a 6-1 loss to Russia, becoming the oldest
player to ever score in World Cup finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
