<HEADLINE> Zabel Wins Another Stage in Tirreno-Adriatico Cycling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 17 (Xinhua) -- German Erik Zabel outpaced his
rivals to win his second stage of the Tirreno-Adriatico cycling
race on Tuesday while Rolf Jaermann held the overall lead with one
day left.
</P>
<P>
Along the relatively flat 164-kilometer route around Civitanova
Marche, some 30 riders still jamed in the leading field with three
kilometers left.
</P>
<P>
Zabel, who won three stages at the 1997 Tour de France, dashed
ahead to edge Italy's Mario Manzoni and Denmark's Rolf Sorensen at
the finish.
</P>
<P>
All were credited with an official time of 4 hours 16 minutes
and 2 seconds as was Switzerland's Jaermann, the 17th man across
the line.
</P>
<P>
However, Jaerman still led the overall standing by four seconds
against Franco Ballerini with only one stage remained, the eighth
162-km stage from Grottammare to San Benedetto del Tronto on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jens Heppner was third with 1:03 behind, and Sorensen ranked
fourth.
</P>
<P>
The Tirreno-Adriatico was considered a major tuneup for the
March 21 Milan-to-San Remo classic, the first event of the 1998
World Cup. 
</P>
