<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Float Europeso Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 18 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines is planning to issue 150 million to 200 million U.S.
dollars worth of Europeso bonds to boost its gross international
reserves, the Manila Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson was quoted as saying
Tuesday the floatation of the Europeso bonds would be on top of
the 1 billion dollars worth of club-loans that it plans to borrow
from a syndicate of international investment banks.
</P>
<P>
The Europeso bond is a peso-denominated debt instrument floated
in international markets.
</P>
<P>
So far, 12 banks have committed to lending 600 million dollars
to the Philippines but the central bank plans to tap other banks
to bring up the amount to 1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
At least two foreign banks have submitted formal offers to
underwrite the central bank's Europeso bond issue, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Department of Finance announced that it would sell
as much as 500 million dollars of 10-year global bonds this year.
</P>
<P>
The plan comes as the central bank aims to boost its foreign
currency reserves to 12 billion dollars in 1998 from the current
9.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Europeso bond may have a maturity of three to five
years, according to Cristina Orbeta, director of the central
bank's external debt management department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
