<HEADLINE> EU Hopes Remaining Tickets Away from French Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Tuesday urged
the World Cup organizers in France to keep the remaining tickets
away from the French fans to calm the furor of the EU community.
</P>
<P>
The EU gave the organizers until the end of the week to present
a plan for the remaining tickets for the finals or face sanctions.
</P>
<P>
As a majority of the 2.5 million tickets had been sold in
France, the executive commission of the 15-nation EU insisted that
the remaining 160,000 seats go exclusively to non-French nationals.
</P>
<P>
"It's necessary to counterbalance major discrimination," said
EU spokesman Stefan Rating.
</P>
<P>
"If they are not forthcoming we will have to proceed," he said,
adding legal steps could result in heavy fines.
</P>
<P>
The CFO has been the target of criticism as tickets for foreign
fans were far away from the huge demand and two-thirds were put on
the French market.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said they received 20 million requests for tickets
for the 64 games but the ten stadiums could only accommodate a
fraction of that demand.
</P>
<P>
Of the 160,000 remaining tickets, 50,000 already are allocated
for foreign soccer federations, with the 110,000 aimed at the
public at large.
</P>
<P>
"The whole issue is whether the `general public' includes
French nationals," said Rating. 
</P>
</TEXT>
