<HEADLINE> Beijing Taxi Riders Turning to Buses for Convenience </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 18 (Xinhua) -- Faced with worsening traffic
congestion, many taxi riders in the Chinese capital began
returning to buses with the advent of a special bus lane last June.
</P>
<P>
The lane is on one of Beijing's busiest streets, Chang'an
Avenue, which runs east-to-west across the heart of Beijing. It is
a major street for public transportation.
</P>
<P>
Traffic authorities say only buses and mini-buses approved by
the police can use the lane, which will help increase bus speed
and encourage more people to ride them.
</P>
<P>
"The buses are faster than before, and they are convenient and
punctual," said Miss Deng, who works for a foreign-funded company
in the east part of the city.
</P>
<P>
Taxis often get jammed on the road during the peak traffic
hours and are difficult to stop on the sides of the street because
of the bus lane limits, she said, "so I gave up taxis and started
taking buses."
</P>
<P>
To date, the city has opened 22 bus routes. Half of those are
double-deckers or air-conditioned. Fifteen more bus routes will be
operational this year. At the same time, urban residents are
returning to the subway and mini buses.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the city's public transportation system
handles 10.2 million passengers per day. Of those, 15 percent are
taxi riders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs India's Agricultural Support Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced here
Tuesday that it will provide 196.8 million U.S. dollars to back
India's National Agricultural Support Project (NATP) in a bid to
accelerate agricultural growth in the country.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to speed up the reform and
strengthening of the country's agricultural technology development
and dissemination system.
</P>
<P>
In the long-run, the project will bring benefits to farmers,
especially the poor, by improving the supply of relevant and
practical agriculture technologies to help increase productivity
and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The project will establish research priority-setting mechanisms
and shift orientation of research to give greater attention to
issues affecting sustainability of production systems, address
stagnation of yield growth in intensive irrigated agriculture and
improve productivity of rain-fed agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is some 239.7 million dollars. Of
the World Bank financing of 196.8 million dollars, a 100 million
dollar interest-free credit will be provided by the International
Development Association (IDA), the Bank's concessionary lending
arm and the remaining 96.8 million dollar loan will be provided by
the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD).
The Indian government will contribute some 42.9 million dollars
for the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
