<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Defends Training Program for Indonesian Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
on Tuesday defended its military program to train Indonesian
troops despite complaints from some lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Congress set a ban in 1992 to ban any programs for training of
foreign troops, but the State Department said the training program
for Indonesian troops was not covered by the six-year-old law.
</P>
<P>
"This training is legal and, in our view, in conformance with
the expressed intent of Congress," State Department spokesman
James Rubin said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
Those joint exercises involving Indonesian troops "enhance
American military readiness and increase U.S. engagement" with
this important Southeast country, he said.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times reported on Tuesday that the Indonesian
forces trained by the Pentagon include a special forces commando
unit called Kopassus.
</P>
<P>
It said the unit had received training from U.S. special
operations soldiers in skills like psychological warfare and
reconnaissance missions.
</P>
<P>
Some members of Congress were quoted by the newspaper as saying
that the administration had been acting in bad faith by continuing
training despite the ban.
</P>
<P>
Nancy Pelosi, a Democratic Representative, said the training
"is certainly not within the spirit" of the 1992 law. "It raises
serious questions about a violation of congressional intent. It
is clear that it is a circumvention of Congress."
</P>
<P>
But Rubin said the administration "has in no way attempted to
mislead Congress, and administration officials have discussed
military exercises and training in Indonesia with relevant
committees on a number of occasions in recent years."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
