<HEADLINE> Clinton Job Approval Rating Remains High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Following former White House
aide Kathleen Willey's charge of impropriety against U.S.
President Bill Clinton, new polls show Americans are divided over
whom to believe, but they continue to give Clinton high marks for
job performance.
</P>
<P>
The polls released Tuesday were the first since Willey aired
her allegations Sunday night on CBS' "60 Minutes" program. Clinton
denied doing anything improper, and the White House released a
barrage of friendly, private notes from Willey to Clinton after
the alleged incident in November 1993.
</P>
<P>
An ABC News poll put Clinton's job approval rating at a 63
percent but showed 50 percent of Americans saying they have a
favorable impression of Clinton, and 46 percent viewing him
unfavorably.
</P>
<P>
A CNN/USA Today/Gallup survey said Clinton's approval rating
had actually increased last week to 67 percent, but the 651 adult
Americans polled Monday were divided over whether to believe the
president or his accuser. 
</P>
