<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Panel Approves Budget Request </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A key U.S. Senate panel
Tuesday approved the administration's request for 1.8 billion U.S.
dollars to keep troops in Bosnia past a now-abandoned June
deadline and to maintain U.S. forces in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The Senate Appropriations Committee split the administration's
spending request into two bills, one containing the 18 billion
U.S. dollars for the IMF and the other containing everything else.
</P>
<P>
Both the bills were approved by a 26-2 vote and sent to the
full Senate, for action perhaps as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
But the committee attached to the spending bill a provision
urging President Clinton to make greater strides in getting allies
to shoulder more costs of confronting Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the panel also tacked on a series of conditions to
the IMF bill intended to pressure the IMF into reforming some of
its practices, calling on the IMF to comply with international
trade obligations in making loans.
</P>
<P>
The Senate version did not include one provision that has drawn
a threatened veto by President Clinton _ abortion restrictions on
international family planning groups. Such a restriction remains
under active consideration in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
The measure also includes 610 million U.S. dollars for disaster
relief, the bulk of it as a result of violent weather caused by El
Nino; and 196 million U.S. dollars to help fix year 2000 computer
problems at the Federal Aviation Administration and the Treasury
Department.
</P>
<P>
The bill includes 1.3 billion U.S. dollars to help offset the
cost to the Pentagon in the current fiscal year of maintaining the
expanded U.S. military presence near Iraq; and 383 million U.S.
dollars for peacekeeping operations in Bosnia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
