<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF: Malnutrition Constitutes Global "Silent Emergency" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Malnutrition constitutes a
global "silent emergency," killing millions every year and sapping
the long-term economic vitality of nations, according to a latest
report of the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
The statistics on malnutrition are grim. Nearly 12 million
children under the age of five die annually, and malnutrition is a
culprit in 55 percent of these deaths, the UNICEF said in The
State of the World's Children 1998.
</P>
<P>
Iron deficiency Anaemia is a contributing factor in over 20
percent of post-birth maternal deaths in Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
About 43 million people worldwide are suffering from varying
degrees of brain damage due to iodine deficiency. Some 226 million
children are stunted (shorter than they should be for their age);
nearly 67 million are estimated to be wasted (weigh less than they
should for their height); and about 183 million weigh less than
they should for the age.
</P>
<P>
The situation in sub-Saharan Africa is more serious than in
other regions of the world, where every third child is underweight
while two out five are stunted, the report says.
</P>
<P>
Mulnutrition is a tangle of two mutually reinforcing factors:
insufficient nutrient intake and illness, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Its root cause, therefore, is poverty at the household,
community and national levels, the report points out.
</P>
<P>
The report urges governments concerned to build widespread
awareness of the roots and consequences of malnutrition, along
with ways of reducing it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Forces Remain in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Defense Secretary William
Cohen said on Tuesday that the American troops will remain in the
Gulf until Iraq could prove to have complied with U.N. resolutions
to destroy all chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraqi officials had repeatedly claimed to have
destroyed their stores of chemical and biological weapons, but he
still believed the arsenal had not been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said on Sunday that there were still 130 tons of chemical
precursors and 15,600 biological munitions kept by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"That's why the international community must remain vigilant.
and that's why we will maintain our forces in the region," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has about 35,000 soldiers, sailors, airmen
and marines on alert in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Cohen did not put any limit on the amount of time U.S. forces
in the Gulf region will remain at their current level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
