<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa to Launch Tourism Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa, Mozambique
and Swaziland will launch a joint tourism investment drive in
early May as part of a multi-million cross-border development
project.
</P>
<P>
At a ministerial meeting on the 600-million-Rand (some 121
million US dollars) Lubombo development project in Mbabane,
Swaziland, South African Tourism Minister Pallo Jordan announced
some of the investment projects.
</P>
<P>
These would include the recently declared world heritage site
at St. Lucia, the yet undeveloped Kosi Bay Lake system, both on
the South Africa's eastern coast, and the Mozambican resort town
of Ponto Do Ouro.
</P>
<P>
The anchor projects would be supported by the publicly-funded
infrastructure developments, including the construction of a new
road along the coastal reserves from Hluhluwe in South Africa's
KwaZulu-Natal province to the Maputo elephant reserve in
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Construction had already begun on the South African portion of
the road and a passenger train service between South Africa's
busy seaport of Durban and Maputo, the capital city of
Mozambique, was introduced last week.
</P>
<P>
Upgrades on South Africa's national coastal highway, the N2
highway, to extend it through Swaziland to Maputo, had also begun
on the South African side of the border.
</P>
<P>
Ministers from the three countries will sign Lubombo protocols
to facilitate rapid cross-border development and traveling.
</P>
<P>
The Lubombo development project is designed to jointly build
up infrastructure, communications, tourism and trade
opportunities in the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Trade and Tourism Minister Oldemiro Baloyi said
that extensive technical planning had gone into packaging the
investment opportunities, including legal, financial, and
marketing requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
