<DOCNO> XIE19980318.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Set up Special Guard Teams to Respond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National Guard will
help local authorities to respond to potential terrorist attacks
from chemical, biological or even nuclear weapons, Defense
Secretary William Cohen said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to establish 10 separate and special National
Guard teams that will be dedicated solely to assisting local
civilian authorities in the event of a chemical or biological
attack," announced Cohen in a speech at the National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
"These teams will arrive quickly, assess the scene and help
ensure these affected areas get the federal assistance" they need,
Cohen said in a speech at the National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
Noting the threat posed by such attacks as the sarin gas attack
on the Tokyo subway or the terrorist bombing of the World Trade
Center in New York, the Defense Secretary said that the nation
must be better prepared against the potential chemical or
biological attacks.
</P>
<P>
The units will help in "providing early assessment, initial
detection, and technical advice to local commanders during an
incident involving weapons of mass destruction, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The National Guard and reserve forces could be deployed to
handle reconnaissance and decontamination. A new office will
oversee coordination of the units with existing ones.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that the Department of Defense is leading a federal
effort to train the first responders in 120 American cities. "The
police, the firefighters, the medical technicians are going to be
first on the scene of an attack. We are now in the process of
helping to prepare these first responders," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Department is requesting 49.2 million U.S. dollars
in next year's budget to pay for the project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
